{"title_page": "Boncho Novakov", "text_new": "{{short description|Bulgarian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Boncho Novakov\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1935|5|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Razgrad]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n}}\n\n'''Boncho Novakov''' ({{lang-bg|\u0411\u043e\u043d\u0447\u043e \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432}}, born 7 May 1935) is a former Bulgarian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1000m time trial|1000m time trial]] at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/no/boncho-novakov-1.html |title=Boncho Novakov Olympic Results |accessdate=4 August 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novakov, Boncho}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Razgrad]]\n\n\n{{Bulgaria-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bulgarian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Boncho Novakov\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1935|5|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Razgrad]], [[Bulgaria]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n}}\n\n'''Boncho Novakov''' ({{lang-bg|\u0411\u043e\u043d\u0447\u043e \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432}}, born 7 May 1935) is a former Bulgarian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 1000m time trial|1000m time trial]] at the [[1960 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/no/boncho-novakov-1.html |title=Boncho Novakov Olympic Results |accessdate=4 August 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Novakov, Boncho}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1960 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Razgrad]]\n\n\n{{Bulgaria-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boncho_Novakov"}
{"title_page": "The Gruffalo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Gruffalo\n| image         = Fairuse Gruffalo.jpg\n| image_size    = 200px\n| caption       = The first edition\n| author        = [[Julia Donaldson]]\n| illustrator   = [[Axel Scheffler]]\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]\n| pub_date      = 23 March 1999\n| pages         = 32\n| isbn          = 0-333-71093-2\n| oclc          = 59379845\n| followed_by   = [[The Gruffalo's Child]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Gruffalo'''''is a children horror film designed to get kids on their toes\n\n''The Gruffalo'' was initially published in 1999 in the United Kingdom by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Children's Books ({{ISBN|0-333-71093-2}}) as a 32-page hardback edition, was followed six months later by a paperback edition, and subsequently by a small-format board book edition. It was penned for readers aged three to seven, and is about 700 words long. It is written in rhyming couplets, featuring repetitive verse with minor variance.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of a [[mouse]]'s walk through the woods unfolds in two phases; in both, the mouse uses clever tricks to evade danger. On his way the mouse encounters several dangerous animals (a [[fox]], an [[owl]], and a [[snake]]). Each of these animals, clearly intending to eat the mouse, invites him back to their home for a meal. The cunning mouse declines each offer. To dissuade further advances, he tells each animal that he has plans to dine with his friend, a \"gruffalo\", a monstrous creature whose favourite food happens to be the relevant animal, and describes the features of the gruffalo's monstrous [[anatomy]]. Frightened that the gruffalo might eat it, each animal flees. Knowing the gruffalo to be fictional, the mouse gloats thus:\n\n: ''Silly old fox/owl/snake, doesn't he know?''\n: ''there's no such thing as a gruffalo!''\n\nAfter getting rid of the last animal, the mouse is shocked to encounter a ''real'' gruffalo \u2013 with all the frightening features the mouse thought that he was inventing. The gruffalo threatens to eat the mouse, but again the mouse is cunning: he tells the gruffalo that he, the mouse, is the scariest animal in the forest. Laughing, the gruffalo agrees to follow the mouse as he demonstrates how feared he is. The two walk through the forest, encountering in turn the animals that had earlier menaced the mouse. Each is terrified by the sight of the pair and runs off \u2013 and each time the gruffalo becomes more impressed with the mouse's apparent toughness. Exploiting this, the mouse threatens to eat the gruffalo, which flees.\n\nThe story is based on a [[Chinese folklore|Chinese folk tale]] of a fox that borrows the terror of a tiger. Donaldson was unable to think of rhymes for \"tiger\" so instead she invented a word that rhymes with \"know\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/childrenandteens/story/0,6000,1292836,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Robert | last=McCrum | title=Interview: Julia Donaldson | date=29 August 2004}}</ref><ref>[http://www.juliadonaldson.co.uk/about.htm Information on Julia Donaldson, children's author and creator of The Gruffalo<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n''The Gruffalo'' won the gold award (in the 0\u20135 years category) of the 1999 [[Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prize]]. It was the UK's best-selling picture book of 2000, won the 2000 Nottingham/Experian Children's Book award, and the ''[[Blue Peter]]'' Best Book To Read Aloud award. The audio version won the Best Children's Audio award in the Spoken Book Awards.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A13729746 h2g2 - 'The Gruffalo' and 'The Gruffalo's Child' - Children's Stories<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  In November 2009 the book was voted \"best bedtime story\" by listeners of BBC Radio 2.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/shows/jeremy-vine/bedtime-stories/ BBC - Radio 2 - Jeremy Vine - Jeremy Vine's Bedtime Stories<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In a 2010 survey by UK charity Booktime, the book came first in a list of children's favourite books.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-11568551 |title=Gruffalo tops list of children's favorite books |accessdate=19 October 2010|work=BBC News  |date=18 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Culture===\nThe Dean Heritage Centre in the [[Forest of Dean]], England was given permission by author Julia Donaldson, illustrator Axel Scheffler and the publisher's Macmillan Children's Books, London, UK, to create a \"Gruffalo trail\" within the national park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dean Heritage Centre|url=http://www.deanheritagecentre.com/events/gruffalotrail.html|publisher=Dean Heritage Centre|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DbgmpLLX?url=http://www.deanheritagecentre.com/events/gruffalotrail.html|archivedate=12 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the time that Julia Donaldson lived in [[Bearsden]], Gruffalo sculptures were installed around [[Kilmardinny|Kilmardinny Loch]] using natural materials, such as a [[beech]] tree trunk for the largest one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glasgowwithkids.co.uk/kilmardinny-loch-gruffalo-bearsden-glasgow-review/|title=Finding the Gruffalo (in Bearsden\u2026)|last=|first=|date=29 October 2015|website=Glasgow With Kids|access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Gruffalo Sculpture Final.jpg|One of the scenes on the Gruffalo Trail, Forest of Dean\nFile:Gruffalo Sculpture, Kilmardinny Loch, Bearsden.JPG|Gruffalo Sculpture, Kilmardinny Loch\n</gallery>\n\n==Translations==\n''The Gruffalo'' has sold over 13&nbsp;million copies in 59 editions worldwide.<ref name=CT28Feb/> Translations include:\n* [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]] (Die Goorgomgaai)\n* [[Basque language|Basque]] (Grufaloa)\n* [[Breton language|Breton]] (Ar Groufalo) \n* [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] (Gruzulak) \n* [[Catalan language|Catalan]] (El Gr\u00fafal)\n* [[Chinese language|Chinese]] (Traditional: \u5495\u5695\u725b, Simplified: \u5495\u565c\u725b, Guluniu)\n* [[Croatian language|Croatian]] (Grubzon)\n* [[Czech language|Czech]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[Doric dialect (Scotland)|Doric Scots]] (The Doric Gruffalo)\n* [[Dutch language|Dutch]] (De Gruffalo)\n* [[Esperanto]] (La Krubalo) \n* [[Estonian language|Estonian]] (Gr\u00fchvel)\n* [[Finnish language|Finnish]] (M\u00f6rkyli) \n* [[French language|French]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[German language|German]] (Der Gr\u00fcffelo)\n* [[Greek language|Greek]] (\u03a4\u03bf \u0393\u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf)\n* [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] (\u05d8\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9)\n* [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] (A graffal\u00f3) \n* [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] (Greppikl\u00f3)\n* [[Irish language|Irish]] (An Garbh\u00e1n)\n* [[Italian language|Italian]] (Il Gruffal\u00f2; first edition was titled ''A spasso col mostro'', Walking with the monster) \n* [[Latin Language|Latin]] (Gruffalo) \n* [[Latvian language|Latvian]] (Bubulis) \n* [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] (Grufas) \n* [[Low German]] (De Gr\u00fcffelo) \n* [[Maltese language|Maltese]] (Il-Gruffl\u00e8)\n* [[Manx language|Manx]] (Yn Gruffalo) \n* [[Maori Language|M\u0101ori]] (Te Tanguruhau)\n* [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] (Gruffaloen)\n* [[Orcadian dialect|Orcadian Scots]] (The Orkney Gruffalo)\n* [[Polish language|Polish]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] (O Grufal\u00e3o)\n* [[Romanian language|Romanian]] (Gruffalo) \n* [[Russian language|Russian]] (\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0444\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n* [[Serbian language|Serbian]] (\u0413\u0440\u043e\u0437\u043e\u043d)\n* [[Slovene language|Slovene]] (Zverjasec)\n* [[Scots language|Scots]] (The Gruffalo)\n* [[Scottish Gaelic]] (An Gruffalo)\n* [[Shetland Scots]] (The Shetland Gruffalo)\n* [[Spanish language|Spanish]] (El Gr\u00fafalo) \n* [[Swedish language|Swedish]] (Gruffalon)\n* [[Turkish language|Turkish]] (Tostoraman)\n* [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] (\u0490\u0440\u0443\u0444\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n* [[Welsh language|Welsh]] (Y Gryffalo)\n* [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n\n==Versions and products==\nThe book was initially sold as an A4 paperback book in 1999, and later as a smaller A5 board book version in 2002. An [[audiobook]] version, narrated by [[Imelda Staunton]], was released in 2002, and a [[jigsaw puzzle|jigsaw]] book version ({{ISBN|1-4050-3496-3}}) was published in 2004. The book is also sold packaged with a gruffalo [[plush toy|soft toy]]. At some point in the print run of the hardcover paper page book, the dialogue was subtly changed. There are two different ISBN numbers for the book. However, the older ISBN number that relates to the original text is no longer available.{{Citation needed|reason=date June 2009|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe \"Gruffalo song\" was released with the audiobook, as a standalone CD single, and on a musical CD with other songs from Donaldson's books.{{Citation needed|reason=date June 2009|date=June 2009}}\n\nDonaldson and Scheffler's sequel, 2004's ''[[The Gruffalo's Child]]'' (which tells the story of the gruffalo's daughter, warned by her father of the terrifying mouse) won the \"Best Children's Book\" award in the 2005 [[British Book Awards]].\n\nA Gruffalo Woodland Trail has been created at the [[Dean Heritage Centre]], Soudley in the [[Forest of Dean]], UK. The trail depicts the scenes from the book and has been carved by local chainsaw artists out of local [[redwood]]. Other Gruffalo-themed woodland walks in Great Britain include Kilmardinny Loch in Bearsden<ref>[http://www.glasgowwithkids.co.uk/kilmardinny-loch-gruffalo-bearsden-glasgow-review/Finding the Gruffalo (in Bearsden\u2026)], Glasgow With Kids, 29 October 2015 </ref> (mentioned above), [[Mount Vernon, Glasgow|Mount Vernon Park]] in [[Glasgow]],<ref>[https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/glasgow-news/vandals-steal-gruffalo-trail-statue-17474311.amp Vandals steal Gruffalo trail statue after ransacking east end community space], Glasgow Live, 26 December 2019</ref> [[Ardkinglas]] in [[Argyll]],<ref>[https://www.ardkinglas.com/the-gruffalo-trail.html The Gruffalo Trail], Ardkinglas.com</ref> [[Whinlatter Forest Park]] in [[Cumbria]],<ref>[https://kidsdaysoutreviews.co.uk/whinlatterforest/ Whinlatter Forest, Braithwaite, Cumbria], Kids Days Out, 16 August 2015 </ref> and several locations managed by [[Forestry England]].<ref>[https://www.forestryengland.uk/gruffalo/gruffalo-orienteering Gruffalo orienteering forest courses], [[Forestry England]]</ref>\n\nA rideable wheeled Gruffalo children's suitcase is manufactured for [[Trunki]]; the case had been featured as a pitch idea on the entrepreneur game show ''[[Dragons' Den]]'' {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}} but was rejected by the show's judges.\n\nDonaldson and Scheffler have collaborated on many other titles; some feature cameos from the Gruffalo in other guises,<ref>{{cite web|title=Julia Donaldson & Axel Scheffler Character Cameos|url=http://donaldson-scheffler-character-cameos.blogspot.co.uk/}}</ref> including as Christmas tree decoration in [[Stick Man]], a drawing by a child in ''[[The Snail and the Whale]]'' and a fish in ''Tiddler''.\n\nA commemorative UK 50p coin featuring \"The Gruffalo\" was issued in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Mint|url=https://www.royalmint.com/our-coins/events/gruffalo/ |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Film===\n{{Main|The Gruffalo (film)}}\nThe book has been [[The Gruffalo (film)|adapted]] into a 27-minute animated film,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8112940.stm | title=Gruffalo to menace Christmas TV |work=BBC   |date=22 June 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> which was broadcast on [[BBC One]] in the UK on 25 December 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/tv/todays-tv/2009/12/24/the-gruffalo-christmas-day-bbc1-5-30pm-115875-21919736/ | title=The Gruffalo, Christmas Day, BBC1, 5.30&nbsp;pm |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |date=24 December 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> This version features [[Robbie Coltrane]] in the title role, [[James Corden]] as the mouse, [[Helena Bonham Carter]] as the mother squirrel narrator, and [[Rob Brydon]] as the Snake.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/06_june/22/gruffalo.shtml | title=The Gruffalo BBC One Christmas special |work=BBC   |date=22 June 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> The production was animated at Studio Soi<ref>[http://www.studiosoi.de Studio Soi]</ref> in Germany and produced through Magic Light Pictures.<ref>[http://www.magiclightpictures.com/the_gruffalo.html Magic Light Pictures \u2013 The Gruffalo]</ref> The film also has the voices of [[John Hurt]] as the Owl and [[Tom Wilkinson]] as the Fox. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for Best Short Film (Animated) on 25 January 2011. The film was also nominated for a [[BAFTA]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ltwmag.com/news/the_gruffalo_oscar_nomination.aspx|title=The Gruffalo Oscar nomination|work=Licensing Today Worldwide|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nThe Gruffalo has been adapted for the stage by Tall Stories theatre company, premiering in 2001. The production has visited the [[West End theatre|West End]] for the last five years, including a staging at the [[Lyric Theatre, London]] during [[Christmas]], most recently 2014. The Tall Stories production has also toured the UK and internationally, including performances at [[Sydney Opera House]] in September 2011 and in the UK most years. It returned to the [[Lyric Theatre, London]] in Summer 2015.\n\nThe Gruffalo has also been adapted for the stage by Meneer Monster. The production has toured around The Netherlands and Belgium in 2014, and will continue in 2015. The Meneer Monster production performed around 250 times. In June 2014 Meneer Monster made a South African version of the Gruffalo with twenty Market Theatre Laboratory students in Johannesburg.\n\n===Ride===\n[[Chessington World of Adventures]] opened a ride called 'The Gruffalo River Ride Adventure', using the original water transit system used on The [[Bubbleworks]] Ride.\n\n==Media appearances==\nThe book appears in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' [[Doctor Who (series 5)|series 5]] episode \"[[The Hungry Earth]]\": Mo reads it to his son, then later by himself before the \"strange event\" happens.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.scottishbooktrust.com/podcasts/video/julia-donaldson Julia Donaldson video podcast], the author discusses The Gruffalo on [http://www.scottishbooktrust.com scottishbooktrust.com]\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/sydney-opera-house/the-mouse-that-roared-20110923-1ko2s.html news story] about the Tall Stories production at [[Sydney Opera House]]\n* [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1236672/The-Gruffalo-creator-Julia-Donaldson-reveals-story-Britains-best-loved-bedtime-story.html The Gruffalo creator Julia Donaldson reveals the story behind Britain's best-loved bedtime story] By JENNY JOHNSTON, Daily Mail, 1 January 2010\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n{{Commons category|Gruffalo}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Gruffalo.ogg|2005-07-22}}\n* [http://www.gruffalo.com/ gruffalo.com], the book's website\n* [http://www.juliadonaldson.co.uk the author's website]\n* [http://www.gruffalolive.com/ thegruffalolive.com], the website for the stage adaptation\n* [http://www.meneermonster.com meneermonster.com], The website of the Dutch theatre company who have adapted the book for theatre\n* [http://tallstories.org.uk/ Tall Stories], the website of the theatre company who have adapted the book for the stage\n* [http://crdp.ac-dijon.fr/The-Gruffalo.html ESL resources for primary school teachers]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-11584795 Who would love a Gruffalo?], Giles Wilson, BBC News Magazine, 22 October 2010\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6DbgmpLLX?url=http://www.deanheritagecentre.com/events/gruffalotrail.html deanheritagecentre.com - gruffalotrail] The Gruffalo trail at the Dean Heritage Centre for 2012\n{{The Gruffalo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruffalo, The}}\n[[Category:1999 children's books]]\n[[Category:British picture books]]\n[[Category:Fantasy books]]\n[[Category:Grizzly bears in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Books adapted into films]]\n[[Category:British children's books]]\n[[Category:Donaldson and Scheffler]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = The Gruffalo\n| image         = Fairuse Gruffalo.jpg\n| image_size    = 200px\n| caption       = The first edition\n| author        = [[Julia Donaldson]]\n| illustrator   = [[Axel Scheffler]]\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Children's literature|Children's]] [[fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]\n| pub_date      = 23 March 1999\n| pages         = 32\n| isbn          = 0-333-71093-2\n| oclc          = 59379845\n| followed_by   = [[The Gruffalo's Child]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Gruffalo''''' is a children's book by writer and playwright [[Julia Donaldson]], illustrated by [[Axel Scheffler]], that tells the story of a mouse, the protagonist of the book, taking a walk in the woods. The book has sold over 13&nbsp;million copies,<ref name=CT28Feb>{{cite news|last1=Marshall|first1=Konrad|title=The Gruffalo author Julia Donaldson reveals where ideas bubble up from|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/entertainment/books/the-gruffalo-author-julia-donaldson-reveals-where-ideas-bubble-up-from-20150224-13m0uk.html|accessdate=2 March 2015|work=The Canberra Times|publisher=Fairfax Media Ltd|date=27 February 2015}}</ref> has won several prizes for children's literature, and has been developed into plays on both the [[West End theatre|West End]] and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] and even an Oscar nominated [[The Gruffalo (film)|animated film]].\n\n''The Gruffalo'' was initially published in 1999 in the United Kingdom by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] Children's Books ({{ISBN|0-333-71093-2}}) as a 32-page hardback edition, was followed six months later by a paperback edition, and subsequently by a small-format board book edition. It was penned for readers aged three to seven, and is about 700 words long. It is written in rhyming couplets, featuring repetitive verse with minor variance.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of a [[mouse]]'s walk through the woods unfolds in two phases; in both, the mouse uses clever tricks to evade danger. On his way the mouse encounters several dangerous animals (a [[fox]], an [[owl]], and a [[snake]]). Each of these animals, clearly intending to eat the mouse, invites him back to their home for a meal. The cunning mouse declines each offer. To dissuade further advances, he tells each animal that he has plans to dine with his friend, a \"gruffalo\", a monstrous creature whose favourite food happens to be the relevant animal, and describes the features of the gruffalo's monstrous [[anatomy]]. Frightened that the gruffalo might eat it, each animal flees. Knowing the gruffalo to be fictional, the mouse gloats thus:\n\n: ''Silly old fox/owl/snake, doesn't he know?''\n: ''there's no such thing as a gruffalo!''\n\nAfter getting rid of the last animal, the mouse is shocked to encounter a ''real'' gruffalo \u2013 with all the frightening features the mouse thought that he was inventing. The gruffalo threatens to eat the mouse, but again the mouse is cunning: he tells the gruffalo that he, the mouse, is the scariest animal in the forest. Laughing, the gruffalo agrees to follow the mouse as he demonstrates how feared he is. The two walk through the forest, encountering in turn the animals that had earlier menaced the mouse. Each is terrified by the sight of the pair and runs off \u2013 and each time the gruffalo becomes more impressed with the mouse's apparent toughness. Exploiting this, the mouse threatens to eat the gruffalo, which flees.\n\nThe story is based on a [[Chinese folklore|Chinese folk tale]] of a fox that borrows the terror of a tiger. Donaldson was unable to think of rhymes for \"tiger\" so instead she invented a word that rhymes with \"know\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/childrenandteens/story/0,6000,1292836,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Robert | last=McCrum | title=Interview: Julia Donaldson | date=29 August 2004}}</ref><ref>[http://www.juliadonaldson.co.uk/about.htm Information on Julia Donaldson, children's author and creator of The Gruffalo<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n''The Gruffalo'' won the gold award (in the 0\u20135 years category) of the 1999 [[Nestl\u00e9 Smarties Book Prize]]. It was the UK's best-selling picture book of 2000, won the 2000 Nottingham/Experian Children's Book award, and the ''[[Blue Peter]]'' Best Book To Read Aloud award. The audio version won the Best Children's Audio award in the Spoken Book Awards.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A13729746 h2g2 - 'The Gruffalo' and 'The Gruffalo's Child' - Children's Stories<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  In November 2009 the book was voted \"best bedtime story\" by listeners of BBC Radio 2.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/shows/jeremy-vine/bedtime-stories/ BBC - Radio 2 - Jeremy Vine - Jeremy Vine's Bedtime Stories<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In a 2010 survey by UK charity Booktime, the book came first in a list of children's favourite books.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-11568551 |title=Gruffalo tops list of children's favorite books |accessdate=19 October 2010|work=BBC News  |date=18 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Culture===\nThe Dean Heritage Centre in the [[Forest of Dean]], England was given permission by author Julia Donaldson, illustrator Axel Scheffler and the publisher's Macmillan Children's Books, London, UK, to create a \"Gruffalo trail\" within the national park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dean Heritage Centre|url=http://www.deanheritagecentre.com/events/gruffalotrail.html|publisher=Dean Heritage Centre|accessdate=5 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DbgmpLLX?url=http://www.deanheritagecentre.com/events/gruffalotrail.html|archivedate=12 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the time that Julia Donaldson lived in [[Bearsden]], Gruffalo sculptures were installed around [[Kilmardinny|Kilmardinny Loch]] using natural materials, such as a [[beech]] tree trunk for the largest one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glasgowwithkids.co.uk/kilmardinny-loch-gruffalo-bearsden-glasgow-review/|title=Finding the Gruffalo (in Bearsden\u2026)|last=|first=|date=29 October 2015|website=Glasgow With Kids|access-date=27 February 2018}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:Gruffalo Sculpture Final.jpg|One of the scenes on the Gruffalo Trail, Forest of Dean\nFile:Gruffalo Sculpture, Kilmardinny Loch, Bearsden.JPG|Gruffalo Sculpture, Kilmardinny Loch\n</gallery>\n\n==Translations==\n''The Gruffalo'' has sold over 13&nbsp;million copies in 59 editions worldwide.<ref name=CT28Feb/> Translations include:\n* [[Afrikaans language|Afrikaans]] (Die Goorgomgaai)\n* [[Basque language|Basque]] (Grufaloa)\n* [[Breton language|Breton]] (Ar Groufalo) \n* [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] (Gruzulak) \n* [[Catalan language|Catalan]] (El Gr\u00fafal)\n* [[Chinese language|Chinese]] (Traditional: \u5495\u5695\u725b, Simplified: \u5495\u565c\u725b, Guluniu)\n* [[Croatian language|Croatian]] (Grubzon)\n* [[Czech language|Czech]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[Doric dialect (Scotland)|Doric Scots]] (The Doric Gruffalo)\n* [[Dutch language|Dutch]] (De Gruffalo)\n* [[Esperanto]] (La Krubalo) \n* [[Estonian language|Estonian]] (Gr\u00fchvel)\n* [[Finnish language|Finnish]] (M\u00f6rkyli) \n* [[French language|French]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[German language|German]] (Der Gr\u00fcffelo)\n* [[Greek language|Greek]] (\u03a4\u03bf \u0393\u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u03bf)\n* [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] (\u05d8\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u05d5\u05ea\u05d9)\n* [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] (A graffal\u00f3) \n* [[Icelandic language|Icelandic]] (Greppikl\u00f3)\n* [[Irish language|Irish]] (An Garbh\u00e1n)\n* [[Italian language|Italian]] (Il Gruffal\u00f2; first edition was titled ''A spasso col mostro'', Walking with the monster) \n* [[Latin Language|Latin]] (Gruffalo) \n* [[Latvian language|Latvian]] (Bubulis) \n* [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]] (Grufas) \n* [[Low German]] (De Gr\u00fcffelo) \n* [[Maltese language|Maltese]] (Il-Gruffl\u00e8)\n* [[Manx language|Manx]] (Yn Gruffalo) \n* [[Maori Language|M\u0101ori]] (Te Tanguruhau)\n* [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] (Gruffaloen)\n* [[Orcadian dialect|Orcadian Scots]] (The Orkney Gruffalo)\n* [[Polish language|Polish]] (Gruffalo)\n* [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] (O Grufal\u00e3o)\n* [[Romanian language|Romanian]] (Gruffalo) \n* [[Russian language|Russian]] (\u0413\u0440\u0443\u0444\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n* [[Serbian language|Serbian]] (\u0413\u0440\u043e\u0437\u043e\u043d)\n* [[Slovene language|Slovene]] (Zverjasec)\n* [[Scots language|Scots]] (The Gruffalo)\n* [[Scottish Gaelic]] (An Gruffalo)\n* [[Shetland Scots]] (The Shetland Gruffalo)\n* [[Spanish language|Spanish]] (El Gr\u00fafalo) \n* [[Swedish language|Swedish]] (Gruffalon)\n* [[Turkish language|Turkish]] (Tostoraman)\n* [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] (\u0490\u0440\u0443\u0444\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n* [[Welsh language|Welsh]] (Y Gryffalo)\n* [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] (\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0430\u043b\u043e)\n\n==Versions and products==\nThe book was initially sold as an A4 paperback book in 1999, and later as a smaller A5 board book version in 2002. An [[audiobook]] version, narrated by [[Imelda Staunton]], was released in 2002, and a [[jigsaw puzzle|jigsaw]] book version ({{ISBN|1-4050-3496-3}}) was published in 2004. The book is also sold packaged with a gruffalo [[plush toy|soft toy]]. At some point in the print run of the hardcover paper page book, the dialogue was subtly changed. There are two different ISBN numbers for the book. However, the older ISBN number that relates to the original text is no longer available.{{Citation needed|reason=date June 2009|date=June 2009}}\n\nThe \"Gruffalo song\" was released with the audiobook, as a standalone CD single, and on a musical CD with other songs from Donaldson's books.{{Citation needed|reason=date June 2009|date=June 2009}}\n\nDonaldson and Scheffler's sequel, 2004's ''[[The Gruffalo's Child]]'' (which tells the story of the gruffalo's daughter, warned by her father of the terrifying mouse) won the \"Best Children's Book\" award in the 2005 [[British Book Awards]].\n\nA Gruffalo Woodland Trail has been created at the [[Dean Heritage Centre]], Soudley in the [[Forest of Dean]], UK. The trail depicts the scenes from the book and has been carved by local chainsaw artists out of local [[redwood]]. Other Gruffalo-themed woodland walks in Great Britain include Kilmardinny Loch in Bearsden<ref>[http://www.glasgowwithkids.co.uk/kilmardinny-loch-gruffalo-bearsden-glasgow-review/Finding the Gruffalo (in Bearsden\u2026)], Glasgow With Kids, 29 October 2015 </ref> (mentioned above), [[Mount Vernon, Glasgow|Mount Vernon Park]] in [[Glasgow]],<ref>[https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/glasgow-news/vandals-steal-gruffalo-trail-statue-17474311.amp Vandals steal Gruffalo trail statue after ransacking east end community space], Glasgow Live, 26 December 2019</ref> [[Ardkinglas]] in [[Argyll]],<ref>[https://www.ardkinglas.com/the-gruffalo-trail.html The Gruffalo Trail], Ardkinglas.com</ref> [[Whinlatter Forest Park]] in [[Cumbria]],<ref>[https://kidsdaysoutreviews.co.uk/whinlatterforest/ Whinlatter Forest, Braithwaite, Cumbria], Kids Days Out, 16 August 2015 </ref> and several locations managed by [[Forestry England]].<ref>[https://www.forestryengland.uk/gruffalo/gruffalo-orienteering Gruffalo orienteering forest courses], [[Forestry England]]</ref>\n\nA rideable wheeled Gruffalo children's suitcase is manufactured for [[Trunki]]; the case had been featured as a pitch idea on the entrepreneur game show ''[[Dragons' Den]]'' {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}} but was rejected by the show's judges.\n\nDonaldson and Scheffler have collaborated on many other titles; some feature cameos from the Gruffalo in other guises,<ref>{{cite web|title=Julia Donaldson & Axel Scheffler Character Cameos|url=http://donaldson-scheffler-character-cameos.blogspot.co.uk/}}</ref> including as Christmas tree decoration in [[Stick Man]], a drawing by a child in ''[[The Snail and the Whale]]'' and a fish in ''Tiddler''.\n\nA commemorative UK 50p coin featuring \"The Gruffalo\" was issued in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Mint|url=https://www.royalmint.com/our-coins/events/gruffalo/ |accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n===Film===\n{{Main|The Gruffalo (film)}}\nThe book has been [[The Gruffalo (film)|adapted]] into a 27-minute animated film,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8112940.stm | title=Gruffalo to menace Christmas TV |work=BBC   |date=22 June 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> which was broadcast on [[BBC One]] in the UK on 25 December 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/tv/todays-tv/2009/12/24/the-gruffalo-christmas-day-bbc1-5-30pm-115875-21919736/ | title=The Gruffalo, Christmas Day, BBC1, 5.30&nbsp;pm |work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |date=24 December 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> This version features [[Robbie Coltrane]] in the title role, [[James Corden]] as the mouse, [[Helena Bonham Carter]] as the mother squirrel narrator, and [[Rob Brydon]] as the Snake.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/06_june/22/gruffalo.shtml | title=The Gruffalo BBC One Christmas special |work=BBC   |date=22 June 2009 | accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> The production was animated at Studio Soi<ref>[http://www.studiosoi.de Studio Soi]</ref> in Germany and produced through Magic Light Pictures.<ref>[http://www.magiclightpictures.com/the_gruffalo.html Magic Light Pictures \u2013 The Gruffalo]</ref> The film also has the voices of [[John Hurt]] as the Owl and [[Tom Wilkinson]] as the Fox. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for Best Short Film (Animated) on 25 January 2011. The film was also nominated for a [[BAFTA]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ltwmag.com/news/the_gruffalo_oscar_nomination.aspx|title=The Gruffalo Oscar nomination|work=Licensing Today Worldwide|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=20 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nThe Gruffalo has been adapted for the stage by Tall Stories theatre company, premiering in 2001. The production has visited the [[West End theatre|West End]] for the last five years, including a staging at the [[Lyric Theatre, London]] during [[Christmas]], most recently 2014. The Tall Stories production has also toured the UK and internationally, including performances at [[Sydney Opera House]] in September 2011 and in the UK most years. It returned to the [[Lyric Theatre, London]] in Summer 2015.\n\nThe Gruffalo has also been adapted for the stage by Meneer Monster. The production has toured around The Netherlands and Belgium in 2014, and will continue in 2015. The Meneer Monster production performed around 250 times. In June 2014 Meneer Monster made a South African version of the Gruffalo with twenty Market Theatre Laboratory students in Johannesburg.\n\n===Ride===\n[[Chessington World of Adventures]] opened a ride called 'The Gruffalo River Ride Adventure', using the original water transit system used on The [[Bubbleworks]] Ride.\n\n==Media appearances==\nThe book appears in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' [[Doctor Who (series 5)|series 5]] episode \"[[The Hungry Earth]]\": Mo reads it to his son, then later by himself before the \"strange event\" happens.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.scottishbooktrust.com/podcasts/video/julia-donaldson Julia Donaldson video podcast], the author discusses The Gruffalo on [http://www.scottishbooktrust.com scottishbooktrust.com]\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/sydney-opera-house/the-mouse-that-roared-20110923-1ko2s.html news story] about the Tall Stories production at [[Sydney Opera House]]\n* [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-1236672/The-Gruffalo-creator-Julia-Donaldson-reveals-story-Britains-best-loved-bedtime-story.html The Gruffalo creator Julia Donaldson reveals the story behind Britain's best-loved bedtime story] By JENNY JOHNSTON, Daily Mail, 1 January 2010\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n{{Commons category|Gruffalo}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Gruffalo.ogg|2005-07-22}}\n* [http://www.gruffalo.com/ gruffalo.com], the book's website\n* [http://www.juliadonaldson.co.uk the author's website]\n* [http://www.gruffalolive.com/ thegruffalolive.com], the website for the stage adaptation\n* [http://www.meneermonster.com meneermonster.com], The website of the Dutch theatre company who have adapted the book for theatre\n* [http://tallstories.org.uk/ Tall Stories], the website of the theatre company who have adapted the book for the stage\n* [http://crdp.ac-dijon.fr/The-Gruffalo.html ESL resources for primary school teachers]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-11584795 Who would love a Gruffalo?], Giles Wilson, BBC News Magazine, 22 October 2010\n* [