{"title_page": "Pope Benedict XVI's visit to the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n[[File:Papal visit in Westminster (17th September 2010).jpg|thumb|right|300px|The papal visit in [[Westminster]], [[London]]]]\n\nThe state visit of Pope Benedict XVI to the United Kingdom was held from 16 to 19 September 2010 and was the first visit by a Pope to Britain after [[Pope John Paul II]] made a [[Pope John Paul II's visit to the United Kingdom|pastoral, rather than state, visit]] in 1982. The visit included the [[beatification]] of [[John Henry Newman|Cardinal Newman]] as a \"pastoral highlight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/catholic.church.seeks.to.clarify.purpose.of.popes.visit/26105.htm |title=Catholic Church seeks to clarify purpose of Pope\u2019s visit 124; Christian News on Christian Today |publisher=Christiantoday.com |date=15 June 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nPope Benedict's visit included meetings with [[Elizabeth II]] ([[Queen of the United Kingdom]] and [[Supreme Governor]] of the [[Church of England]]), the [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Alex Salmond]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] [[Rowan Williams]], [[British Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] and [[UK Conservative Party|Conservative Party]] leader [[David Cameron]], and leaders of the other main political parties.\n\nThe Pope's itinerary included open air Masses in Glasgow and Birmingham, a youth vigil in Hyde Park in London, and Mass at Westminster Cathedral in London, attended by over 200,000 people.\n\n==Invitation and planning==\n{{Expand section|date=September 2010}}\nAn invitation to visit Britain was extended to [[Pope Benedict XVI]] by then [[Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] in February 2009. The Pope's visit featured in the debates between party leaders in April 2010, prior to the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], where all three party leaders expressed support for the visit, while expressing disagreement with some of the Pope's views.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/23_04_10_seconddebate.pdf Second prime ministerial debate, 22 April 2010, Transcript] ''[[BBC News]]'' 23 April 2010</ref>\n\nAnjoum Noorani of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] was originally a key contact between the [[British Government]] and the papal visit team. However, he was suspended from overseas postings and given a final warning, to last for five years, after approving the [[Foreign Office papal visit memo|sending of a memo]] written by Steven Mulvain, a 23-year-old Oxford graduate, mocking the visit.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/7804506/Diplomat-who-sent-Pope-condom-memo-given-final-warning-and-banned-from-overseas-postings.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Diplomat who sent Pope 'condom' memo given final warning and banned from overseas postings | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=6 June 2010}}</ref> Subsequently the new Government appointed liberal Catholic<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/damianthompson/100046639/lord-patten-im-like-lot-of-catholics-i-dont-agree-with-everything-the-vatican-says/ | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Lord Patten: 'I'm like lot of Catholics. I don't agree with everything the Vatican says' | date=8 July 2010}}</ref> [[Chris Patten|Lord Patten]] to get the visit back on track following a series of setbacks.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/7803820/Lord-Patten-will-co-ordinate-Pope-Benedict-XVIs-trip-to-Britain.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Lord Patten will co-ordinate Pope Benedict XVI's trip to Britain | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=4 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ticketed events===\nThere were three specific ticketed events open to the public during the Pope's visit. These were a [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in [[Bellahouston Park]], Glasgow, on the afternoon of Thursday 16 September, an evening prayer vigil in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], London, on Saturday 18 September, and the Mass of Beatification of John Henry Newman in Cofton Park, [[Longbridge]], Birmingham, on Sunday 19 September.\n\nIn contrast with the previous Papal visit to Britain, that of Pope John Paul II in 1982, where anyone could attend open-air events, there was tight security for the 2010 Papal visit, with all attendees required to register in advance through their parish and to attend in a group with a 'Pilgrim Leader' from that parish, who as leader had the responsibility to vouch for all members of his group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Attending-Events/How-can-I-see-the-Pope-in-the-UK |title=Article-How can I see the Pope in the UK? |publisher=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> All registered attendees received a 'Pilgrim Pass', required for admission to events. Non-Catholics were permitted to attend, by contacting their local parish.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckford |first=Martin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7873291/Non-Catholics-encouraged-to-take-part-in-Popes-visit-to-Britain.html |title=Non-Catholics encouraged to take part in Pope's visit to Britain |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe Mass of Beatification in Cofton Park was originally arranged for [[Coventry Airport]], with a capacity of up to 250,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/coventry_warwickshire/8576825.stm |title=Mass to be held at Coventry Airport by Pope Benedict |publisher=BBC News |date=19 March 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The planned event at the airport, which had seen 350,000 attend the visit of Pope John Paul II in 1982,<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WggOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l20DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6855,6458500]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref> was the subject of an Isle of Man commemorative stamp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/catholiclife/2010/08/13/newman-and-papal-visit-receive-stamp-of-approval/ |title=Newman and papal visit receive stamp of approval |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> However the event was switched to the much smaller Cofton Park, [[Longbridge]], a switch that the church denied was to reduce costs, instead stating that Cofton Park had a greater connection to Newman, who had lived in the area and walked around the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10509127 |title=Pope's UK visit 'could cost taxpayers \u00a312m' |work=BBC News |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Costs===\nThe visit of the Pope was the first state visit of a Pope to Britain; the visit of his predecessor, Pope John Paul II, had been a pastoral visit, and as such the British government did not pay the costs of that visit, although expenses were incurred by local governments in areas that he visited.<ref name=visit1982>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Js8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BNkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3067,6922073|title=The Fort Scott Tribune - Google News Archive Search|website=News.google.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe final cost to the British taxpayer (excluding policing costs) of the visit was \u00a310 million.<ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news|author=Riazat Butt, religious affairs correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/oct/28/catholic-church-papal-visit-uk |title=Catholic church struggles with cost of pope's visit to UK |work=The Guardian |date=28 October 2010 |accessdate=5 December 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=bbcCosts>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11305217 |title=David Cameron offers 'warm welcome' to Pope in video |work=BBC News |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The cost to the taxpayer was criticised, with a [[ComRes]] poll showing that 76% of people in the UK agreed with the statement that 'The Pope is a religious figure so the taxpayer should not be contributing to the costs of his visit'.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://campaigndirector.moodia.com/Client/Theos/Files/TheosPopePoll.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714113841/http://campaigndirector.moodia.com/Client/Theos/Files/TheosPopePoll.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2011  }}</ref> The cost was defended by the Archbishop of Westminster, leader of the Catholic Church in England and Wales, who said that it was right for the government to pay for official State Visits,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11191386 |title=Archbishop says UK taxpayer should help fund Pope visit |work=BBC News |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> as well as by Lord Patten, who said that the cost compared favourably with the \u00a320 million spent on the [[2009 G-20 London Summit]].<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i399yZzlQndOhF_77tHM7TeLAMEwD9I3OCP81]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref> The visit was predicted to cost Edinburgh City council \u00a3400,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blackley |first=Michael |url=http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/topstories/Pope39s-visit-to-Edinburgh-will.6456024.jp |title=Pope's visit to Edinburgh will cost city \u00a3400k - Edinburgh Evening News |publisher=edinburghnews.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe financial benefits as well as costs of the Papal visit were reported, with the councillor coordinating the visit to Birmingham, which incurred \u00a380,000 in direct costs, estimated before the event a \u00a312.5 million boost to the city,<ref>{{cite news |author=Neil Elkes |url=http://www.birminghampost.net/dailybulletin/news2/2010/09/07/pope-visit-worth-12-5-million-to-birmingham-s-economy-65233-27221936/ |title=Pope visit worth \u00a312.5 million to Birmingham's economy |work=Birmingham Post |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> while Scott Taylor of Glasgow City Marketing Bureau said that there was a direct \u00a34.25m benefit to Glasgow, with further valuable publicity from the resultant media coverage of the city.\n\nIt was announced in July that attendees at events would be charged for a compulsory 'Pilgrim Pack', including commemorative items, in order to fund transport costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/07/14/faithful-urged-to-apply-as-soon-as-possible-for-papal-visit-places/ |title=Catholics urged to apply as soon as possible for papal visit places |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=14 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The costs were \u00a35 for the Hyde Park vigil (which did not include transport), \u00a325 to attend the Cofton Park event and \u00a320 to attend Bellahouston Park Mass.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckford |first=Martin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8000247/Pope-visit-Church-blames-early-start-for-low-ticket-sales.html |title=Pope visit: Church blames early start for low ticket sales |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref> The \u00a320 charge for Bellahouston Park was levied on the parish, which had discretion as to whether it recouped the cost directly from attendees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/content/download/9874/64535/file/PAPAL%20MASS%20BELLAHOUSTON%20FAQS.pdf|format=PDF|title=Papal Mass \u2013 Bellahouston Park : Thursday 16th September 2010 : Frequently Asked Questions|website=Thepapalvisit.org.uk|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309071414/http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/content/download/9874/64535/file/PAPAL%20MASS%20BELLAHOUSTON%20FAQS.pdf|archive-date=9 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The charges were said to be the first ever levied for attending Papal events,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/07/28/catholics-pay-attend-big-events-england-popes-visit-september/ |title=Pilgrims must pay to attend 2 big events in England during pope's visit in September |work=Fox News |date=7 April 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> and came amid reports that the church was \u00a32.6 million short of its donation target.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/catholic-church-struggles-to-raise-funds-for-popes-visit-2052311.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Catholic Church struggles to raise funds for Pope's visit | first=Jerome | last=Taylor | date=14 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe cost to the Catholic Church was \u00a310 million,<ref name=\"guardian1\"/><ref name=bbcCosts /> against the \u00a37 million published on the Papal Visit website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/catholic-church-struggles-to-raise-funds-for-popes-visit-2052311.html |title=Catholic Church struggles to raise funds for Pope's visit |work=The Independent |date=14 August 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London |first=Jerome |last=Taylor}}</ref> The bulk of the \u00a37m, \u00a35.2m was for staging the three large-scale public events, a further \u00a30.6m for three smaller pastoral events, with the remaining \u00a31.2m covering evangelism, planning and communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepapalvisit.com/Donate/Why-does-the-Church-need-to-raise-7m-and-what-will-it-be-spent-on |title=Article-Why does the Church need to raise \u00a37m and what will it be spent on? |work=Thepapalvisit.com |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> \u00a31.1 million was raised through a [[Pentecost]] Sunday special collection in churches and \u00a34m from wealthy individual donors. As of November 2010 the church had a \u00a33.5m shortfall, due to be repaid to the Government by April 2011.<ref name=\"guardian1\"/>\n\n==Visit==\n\n===Scotland===\n\n====16 September====\nPope Benedict XVI began his official visit in [[Scotland]] at [[Edinburgh Airport]] on 16 September, where he was greeted by [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] and the Archbishops of [[Vincent Nichols|Westminster]] and [[Keith O'Brien|St Andrews and Edinburgh]]. He then met [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] for the first time at [[Holyrood Palace]] in [[Edinburgh]], the Queen's official residence in Scotland, with the ceremonial [[Guard of honour]] formed by the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], the [[Royal Company of Archers]] and the [[High Constables and Guard of Honour of the Palace of Holyroodhouse|High Constables of Holyroodhouse]].\n\nIn his speech at Holyrood Palace, the Pope associated [[State atheism|atheist extremism]] with [[Nazism]], causing controversy.<ref name=audiencequeen>{{cite web|url=https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/speeches/2010/september/documents/hf_ben-xvi_spe_20100916_incontro-autorita_en.html |title=Audience with H.M. The Queen and State Reception Address of His Holiness Benedict XVI |publisher=Vatican.va |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11332515 Row after Pope's remarks on atheism and Nazis] ''[[BBC News]]'', 16 September 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/297690 Fury as Pope appears to equate UK atheism with Nazism] ''Digital Journal'', 17 September 2010</ref><ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/Religion/post/2010/09/pope-benedict-atheists-nazis-richard-dawkins/1 Atheist Dawkins rages at pope tying godless, Nazis] ''[[USA Today]]'', 17 September 2010</ref> The Pope said:\n{{cquote|Even in our own lifetime, we can recall how [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and her leaders stood against a [[Nazi Germany|Nazi tyranny]] that wished to eradicate [[God]] from society and denied our [[humanism|common humanity]] to many, especially the [[Jews]], who were thought unfit to live. I also recall the regime\u2019s attitude to Christian pastors and religious who spoke the truth in love, opposed the Nazis and paid for that opposition with their lives. As we reflect on the sobering lessons of the atheist extremism of the twentieth century, let us never forget how the exclusion of God, religion and virtue from public life leads ultimately to a truncated vision of man and of society and thus to a \u201creductive vision of the person and his destiny\u201d.<ref name=\"audiencequeen\" />\n}}\n\nA parade for [[Saint Ninian]]'s day was held at 11am, the route beginning on Regent Road, Edinburgh, and proceeding along [[Princes Street]]. Attendance was open to all, with a parade of school children and figures from Scotland's Christian history, in honour of St Ninian of Galloway, who brought Christianity to Scotland from Rome in the fifth century. After the parade, which was attended by around 125,000 people, the Pope proceeded by Popemobile<ref name=popemobile>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Popemobile-Routes |title=Pope Benedict XVI-Popemobile Routes |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> to have lunch with [[Keith O'Brien|Cardinal O'Brien]] at his home before travelling by car to [[Glasgow]].\n\nThe Pope was greeted by the [[Mario Conti|Archbishop of Glasgow]] for the ticketed Mass of the Feast of St Ninian in [[Bellahouston Park]]. [[Susan Boyle]] and [[Pop Idol]] winner [[Michelle McManus]] performed before the start of the Mass.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} Attendance was around 65,000 people.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cramb |first=Auslan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8007705/Pope-visit-thousands-make-the-pilgrimage-to-Bellahouston-Park.html |title=Pope visit: thousands make the pilgrimage to Bellahouston Park |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref> The Pope flew from [[Glasgow Airport]] to London [[Heathrow airport]] that evening.<ref name=itinerary>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Events-Timeline |title=Article-Events Timeline / 2010 Visit |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===England===\n\n====17 September====\nOn the second day of his visit to the United Kingdom the Pope began the day with a private Mass in the chapel at [[54 Parkside]], Wimbledon, south west London, the official residence of the [[Nunciature to Great Britain|Apostolic Nunciature to Great Britain]]. His first public engagement was a celebration of Catholic education with a visit to address educators and students at [[St Mary's University, Twickenham]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stmarys.ac.uk/about/papal-visit/overview.aspx|title=The 2010 Papal Visit &#124; St Mary's University, Twickenham |publisher=Stmarys.ac.uk |date=17 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> which was followed by a meeting with people of faith in the university's Waldegrave Drawing Room.\n\nHe became the first Pope to enter [[Lambeth Palace]], where he met the [[Rowan Williams|Archbishop of Canterbury]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} He made the journey from Lambeth Palace to the [[Palace of Westminster]] by Popemobile,<ref name=popemobile /> making an address to Civil Society from the spot in [[Westminster Hall]] where [[Thomas More|St Thomas More]] died a martyr's death in 1535, being accused of high treason for holding to his Catholic faith in refusing to acknowledge the validity of the [[First Succession Act|Act of Succession]].\n\nIn the evening there was an ecumenical celebration of evening prayer at [[Westminster Abbey]] with representatives from all the main Christian churches including the Greek Orthodox, Coptic and Free Churches. He later venerated the tomb of [[Edward the Confessor]] at the Abbey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/press/news/news/2010/september/historic-abbey-service-for-pope |title=Historic Abbey Service for Pope |publisher=Westminster Abbey |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n====18 September====\n[[File:Hyde Park Vigil.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Pope Benedict leads the vigil in Hyde Park.]]\n[[File:Hyde Park Vigil 80000.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Some of the 80,000 attending the vigil in Hyde Park.]]\nThe Pope began the day with meetings with [[David Cameron]], Prime Minister, [[Nick Clegg]], as Deputy Prime Minister, and [[Harriet Harman]], Acting Leader of the Opposition. This was followed with morning Mass in [[Westminster Cathedral]]. In his sermon, the Pope referenced [[Catholic sexual scandal in the United Kingdom|sexual abuse by priests]], saying: \"Here, too, I think of the immense suffering caused by the abuse of children, especially within the church and by her ministers. Above all, I express my deep sorrow to the innocent victims of these unspeakable crimes\", saying \"I also acknowledge with you the shame and humiliation which all of us have suffered because of these sins\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-sermon-westminster-cathedral |title=Pope Benedict XVI's sermon at Westminster Cathedral |work=The Guardian |date= 18 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nAfter Mass, the Pope used the middle part of the day to meet five victims of child sex abuse at the Apostolic Nunciature, apologising to them and describing the Church's measures to protect young people.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pigott |first=Robert |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11361749 |title=What has the Pope's visit achieved? 19 September 2010 |work=BBC News |date=19 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The meeting had been planned before the Pope's visit, and time was left free in his schedule to allow for it.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn the evening the Pope visited St Peter's Residence for Older People, run by [[Little Sisters of the Poor]]. The Pope travelled to the day's main event, the ticketed Hyde Park Prayer Vigil on the Eve of the Beatification of Cardinal Newman, by Popemobile.<ref name=popemobile /> The vigil was attended by 80,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2010/09/19/the-pope-apologises-to-abuse-victims-as-80-000-pray-in-london-park-86908-22572592/ |title=The Pope apologises to abuse victims as 80,000 pray in London park |work=The Daily Record |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The Pope's speech described Newman's life's work \"as a struggle against the growing tendency to view religion as a purely private and subjective matter, a question of personal opinion\", stating that it was a lesson for today, in which \"an intellectual and moral relativism threatens to sap the very foundations of our society\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/09/18/papal-visit-2010-popes-address-at-hyde-park-vigil-full-text/ |title=Papal Visit 2010: Pope\u2019s Address at Hyde Park Vigil \u2013 full text |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=18 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n====19 September====\n[[File:Stage preparations, Cofton Park, 090910, cropped.JPG|thumb|right|Stage being prepared for ceremony in Cofton Park]]\nThe final day of the Pope's visit saw the Pope fly by helicopter from London to [[Birmingham]] for the main event of his visit, the [[beatification]] of [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[John Henry Newman]] in [[Cofton Park]] in Birmingham. Local residents were required to carry vehicle passes as well as to carry proof of identity in order to leave their own homes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peek |first=Sitala |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-11303899 |title=Pope's visit: historic event or one to avoid? |work=BBC News |date=15 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> Attendance at the event was approximately 55,000,<ref>{{cite web |last=Hesketh |first=Jane |url=http://www.itv.com/central-west/pope-at-cofton-park51831/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127024240/http://www.itv.com/central-west/pope-at-cofton-park51831/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 January 2013 |title=Central Regional News (ITV Central Tonight) - ITV Local |publisher=Itv.com |date=19 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 }}</ref> a figure said to have been reduced by the requirement to arrive at the location between 3am and 7am on special coaches for the 10am start.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/uk/administration-problems-blamed-for-pope-visit-ticket-slump-14947215.html |title='Administration problems' blamed for Pope visit ticket slump |work=Belfast Telegraph |date=13 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Cofton Park Mass was followed by a private visit to [[Birmingham Oratory]], founded by John Henry Newman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Itinerary/19-September-2010/The-Birmingham-Oratory |title=The Birmingham Oratory |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920163138/http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Itinerary/19-September-2010/The-Birmingham-Oratory |archive-date=20 September 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The visit was preceded by controversy due to the exiling of three priests to monasteries in separate parts of the world.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7956204/Popes-visit-could-be-overshadowed-by-exile-of-Birmingham-priests.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope's visit could be overshadowed by exile of Birmingham priests | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe visit concluded with lunch and a meeting with the bishops of England, Scotland and Wales at [[St Mary's College, Oscott]]. The Pope gave a final speech at [[Birmingham Airport, England|Birmingham Airport]], before departing for [[Rome]] on a chartered [[Alitalia]] Airbus A320. [[British Airways]], as UK flag carrier, would have been the usual choice for a state Papal visit, but they were reportedly rejected due to concerns about strikes.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Other events===\nThe Pope's schedule reportedly included free time to allow for the 83-year-old to take naps.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/popes-uk-visit-schedule-to-contain-nap-breaks-2055909.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Pope's UK visit schedule to contain nap breaks | first=Jerome | last=Taylor | date=18 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the visit, an exhibition of [[Sistine Chapel#Raphael's tapestries|Raphael's tapestries]] for the [[Sistine Chapel]] took place at London's [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] from 8 September to 17 October 2010 where they were displayed for the first time alongside the [[Raphael cartoons]] used to make them; the cartoons having been in the British [[Royal Collection]] since 1623. This followed a reported scaling-back of earlier plans for a large exhibition of Vatican artworks at London's [[Royal Academy]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/damianthompson/100047995/popes-visit-what-happened-to-the-major-exhibition-of-vatican-treasures-at-the-royal-academy/ | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope's visit: What happened to the major exhibition of Vatican treasures at the Royal Academy? | date=21 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-terrorism arrests==\nOn 17 September 2010 the [[Metropolitan Police]] arrested five street cleaners under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] in a pre-dawn raid at a London cleaning depot, in a suspected terrorist plot against the Pope on the second day of his state visit; a sixth person was arrested later in the day at his home \"on suspicion of the commission, preparation or instigation of acts of terrorism\".<ref>{{Cite news| title = Six held over Pope terror alert | date = 17 September 2010 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11346001 | work = BBC News | accessdate = 17 September 2010}}</ref> The men, aged between 26 and 50, had been working as street cleaners for contractors [[Veolia Environnement]], on behalf of [[Westminster City Council]] and were based at the Chiltern Street depot in [[Marylebone]].\n\nThe suspects were questioned at an unidentified London police station. The police did not uncover any hazardous items during an initial search of the business premises and other properties.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i399yZzlQndOhF_77tHM7TeLAMEwD9I9RPO00 | location=London | agency=Associated Press | title=6 arrested in UK in alleged terror threat to pope | first=Nicole | last=Winfield | date=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to police some of the suspects were thought to be immigrants to Britain, from a variety of nations including a number from Algeria.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8010002/Pope-visit-sixth-man-arrested-over-alleged-assassination-plot.html | location=London | work=The Telegraph | title=Pope visit: sixth man arrested over alleged assassination plot | first=Duncan | last=Gardham | date=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nAll the men were released without charge before the Pope's visit ended. It turned out they were arrested after joking about how the [[Popemobile]] could not withstand an [[Rocket-propelled grenade|RPG]] attack.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Response==\n\n===Support===\n[[File:Flag of the Vatican City flying in Bradford (21st September 2010).jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Flag of Vatican City]] flying in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] in honour of the papal visit.]]\nThe visit saw support from a range of people and organisations, including several leaders within other religions. The President of the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] UK, Rafiq Hayat stated that \"Religious leaders have a pivotal role to play in promoting peace and serving humanity. Indeed religions have far more commonalities than differences and we welcome moves that will help forge unity and foster greater understanding.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sys-con.com/node/1537040|title=UK Muslim Leader Welcomes Visit by Pope|date= 17 September 2010|accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nVivian Wineman, President of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], said \"In an age where scepticism and ill-will towards religion is rising, it will be an excellent opportunity to demonstrate that there is much to unite people of faith and much that can be achieved when we work together for the greater good not only of our members, but for society as a whole.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcdow.org.uk/papalvisit/blog/?25|title=Papal visit to Great Britain|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=15 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928133035/http://www.rcdow.org.uk/papalvisit/blog/?25|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMedia coverage of the visit, which was largely critical before the event, was more positive during and following the Pope's visit. A BBC News correspondent noted that 'there was a tangible sense of relief, even of euphoria, among Pope Benedict's entourage during the return flight to Rome from Birmingham'.<ref>{{cite news|last=Willey |first=David |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11372501 |title=Pope's visit is deemed to challenge stereotypes |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=20 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition===\n{{Further|Anti-Catholicism in the United Kingdom|Criticism of the Catholic Church}}\n[[File:2010 protest the pope rally.png|thumb|right|Protest during the Pope's visit]]\n\nThe visit was opposed by a range of people and organisations including some Protestants, LGBT and secular groups due to a number of reasons, such as the Church's policies on the [[ordination of women]], [[Homosexuality and Roman Catholicism|homosexuality]], [[Catholic contraception|contraception]] and [[Roman Catholic Church and AIDS|AIDS]], as well as complaints over [[Catholic sex abuse cases|historical sexual abuse of children by Catholic priests]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|last=Wynne |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7981933/Public-believes-taxpayers-should-not-fund-papal-visit.html |title=Public believes taxpayers should not fund papal visit |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2010/06/03/church-costs-for-popes-visit-out-of-control/ |title=Church costs for Pope\u2019s visit \u2018out of control\u2019 - from Pink News |work=Pink News |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> Former DUP leader [[Ian Paisley]] (known for his staunch [[Anti-Catholicism]] in [[Northern Ireland]]) called the visit a \"mistake\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10484122 |title=Pope Benedict XVI UK visit a 'mistake' says Ian Paisley |work=BBC News |date=2 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> and the principal of Scotland's [[Free Church Training College]] said the visit airbrushed the [[Protestant Reformation]] out of history and dishonoured reformer and nationalist [[John Knox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/07/14/faithful-urged-to-apply-as-soon-as-possible-for-papal-visit-places/ |title=Catholics urged to apply as soon as possible for papal visit places |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=14 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> On the eve of the visit, a letter by 50 public figures argued that the Pope's tour should not have been accorded the status of a state visit.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/15/pope-uk-state-visit-protest Pope's visit: pontiff should not be 'honoured' with state visit] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 15 September 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/15/harsh-judgments-on-pope-religion |title=Letter by 50 public figures for not giving the honour of state to Pope |work=The Guardian |date= 15 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nA number of groups, including the [[British Humanist Association]] and the [[National Secular Society]] organised a campaign of protests against the visit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.protest-the-pope.org.uk/ |title=Protest The Pope |publisher=Protest The Pope |accessdate=18 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813034024/http://www.protest-the-pope.org.uk/ |archivedate=13 August 2010  }}</ref> The Roman Catholic [[pressure group]] \"Catholic Women's Ordination\" arranged for London buses to carry advertisements encouraging the Pope to \"Ordain Women Now\"<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/22/london-bus-female-ordination-pope | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=London buses to carry female ordination advert during pope's visit. | first=Riazat | last=Butt | date=22 July 2010}}</ref> and also planned further unspecified lobbying action. Religious and secular correspondents noted that only 3 women appeared at Lambeth Palace to support the ordination of women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-womens-ordination.org.uk/news.htm#Pope |title=Local Groups |work=Catholic-womens-ordination.org.uk |date= |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Richard dawkins speaking at the protest the pope rally 2010.png|thumb|right|[[Richard Dawkins]] speaking at the protest, with [[Peter Tatchell]] on the left at the back.]]\n[[Richard Dawkins]] gave a speech to over 10,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-protest|title=Protest the Pope rally sees 10,000 march through London's streets|first=Tracy|last=Mcveigh|date=18 September 2010|accessdate=26 November 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> people at the \"Protest the Pope\" rally, declaring the pope \"an enemy of humanity\", and countering the Pope's claim that [[the holocaust]] was the result of atheism by arguing that [[Hitler]] was a Roman Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://richarddawkins.net/articles/521113-ratzinger-is-an-enemy-of-humanity |title=Dawkins speech |publisher=Richarddawkins.net |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Science |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/punctuated-equilibrium/2010/sep/20/1 |title=Richard Dawkins' unedited speech at 'Protest the Pope' march in London |work=The Guardian |date= 20 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> Dawkins had previously supported a call for the Pope's arrest for \"crimes against humanity\", an idea first proposed by [[Christopher Hitchens]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://richarddawkins.net/videos/5434-christopher-hitchens-arrest-the-pope | title=Christopher Hitchens: Arrest The Pope!}}</ref> and described by a former editor of the ''[[Catholic Herald]]'' as \"lunatic\",<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8614232.stm | work=BBC News | title=Dawkins backs plan to arrest Pope | date=13 April 2010}}</ref> and human rights lawyer [[Geoffrey Robertson]] was reported to have looked at options to [[Geoffrey Robertson#Putting Pope Benedict XVI on trial|charge the Pope]] over his alleged cover-up of sexual abuse in the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2010/apr/13/pope-prosecution-dawkins |title=The pope should stand trial |work=The Guardian |date= 13 April 2010|accessdate=18 September 2010 |location=London |first=Richard |last=Dawkins}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, the UK government announced plans to change the law on universal jurisdiction to prevent the issue of an arrest warrant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/295022 |title=UK government acts to prevent arrest of Pope |publisher=Digitaljournal.com |date=23 July 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Attempts to make a citizen's arrest on the Pope were abandoned by [[Peter Tatchell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/peter-tatchell-scraps-idea-of-making-citizens-arrest-on-the-pope-2074273.html |title=Peter Tatchell scraps idea of making citizen's arrest on the Pope |work=The Independent |date= 9 September 2010|accessdate=17 September 2010 |location=London |first=Jerome |last=Taylor}}</ref> Members of [[Muslims Against Crusades]] protested against the Pope in London.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Multiple authors|title=Pope Benedict XVI's UK visit: Day three|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-london|accessdate=10 April 2016|work=The Guardian|agency=Reuters|date=18 September 2010}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' reported that around 10,000 protesters marched in London against the Pope's visit on 18 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tracy Mcveigh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-protest |title=Protest the Pope rally sees 10,000 march through London's streets |work=The Guardian |date= 18 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nThe [[BBC]] marked the visit with documentaries including:<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mandrake/7866684/Pope-Benedict-XVI-about-to-be-put-on-trial-by-the-BBC.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope Benedict XVI about to be put on trial by the BBC | first=Tim | last=Walker | date=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/03/bbc-papal-visit | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=BBC to mark Pope's UK visit with documentary on clerical abuse scandals | first=Tara | last=Conlan | date=3 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n* ''Vatican: The Hidden World'', a profile of the [[Holy See|Vatican]] with unprecedented access given\n* ''The Real Joseph Ratzinger'', a papal profile\n*''Newman: Saint or Sinner?'', a documentary about [[Cardinal Newman]]\n*''Benedict - Trials of a Pope'', a documentary about the life of the Pope<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00ttj16 |title=Benedict: Trials of a Pope |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Catholicism|Christianity}}\n*[[List of journeys of Pope Benedict XVI]]\n*[[Roman Catholicism in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Foreign Office papal visit memo]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikinews|Pope Benedict XVI heads to the UK amid protests}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111119175338/http://thepapalvisit.co.uk/ Apostolic journey to Britain] - official website from [[Catholic Church in England and Wales]]\n*[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/travels/2010/index_regno-unito_en.htm Apostolic Journey to the United Kingdom] - official website from the [[Holy See]]\n\n<br />\n{{Benedict XVI}}\n{{Elizabeth II}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope Benedict Xvi's Visit To The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Pope Benedict XVI]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the Holy See]]\n[[Category:History of Christianity in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2010 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2010 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Foreign trips by popes|Benedict XVI, United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Holy See\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic visits to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:September 2010 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n[[File:Papal visit in Westminster (17th September 2010).jpg|thumb|right|300px|The papal visit in [[Westminster]], [[London]]]]\n\nThe state visit of Pope Benedict XVI to the United Kingdom was held from 16 to 19 September 2010 and was the first visit by a Pope to Britain after [[Pope John Paul II]] made a [[Pope John Paul II's visit to the United Kingdom|pastoral, rather than state, visit]] in 1982. The visit included the [[beatification]] of [[John Henry Newman|Cardinal Newman]] as a \"pastoral highlight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/catholic.church.seeks.to.clarify.purpose.of.popes.visit/26105.htm |title=Catholic Church seeks to clarify purpose of Pope\u2019s visit 124; Christian News on Christian Today |publisher=Christiantoday.com |date=15 June 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nPope Benedict's visit included meetings with [[Elizabeth II]] ([[Queen of the United Kingdom]] and [[Supreme Governor]] of the [[Church of England]]), the [[First Minister of Scotland]] [[Alex Salmond]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] [[Rowan Williams]], [[British Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] and [[UK Conservative Party|Conservative Party]] leader [[David Cameron]], and leaders of the other main political parties.\n\nThe Pope's itinerary included open air Masses in Glasgow and Birmingham, a youth vigil in Hyde Park in London, and Mass at Westminster Cathedral in London, attended by over 200,000 people.\n\n==Invitation and planning==\n{{Expand section|date=September 2010}}\nAn invitation to visit Britain was extended to [[Pope Benedict XVI]] by then [[Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] in February 2009. The Pope's visit featured in the debates between party leaders in April 2010, prior to the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], where all three party leaders expressed support for the visit, while expressing disagreement with some of the Pope's views.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/23_04_10_seconddebate.pdf Second prime ministerial debate, 22 April 2010, Transcript] ''[[BBC News]]'' 23 April 2010</ref>\n\nAnjoum Noorani of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] was originally a key contact between the [[British Government]] and the papal visit team. However, he was suspended from overseas postings and given a final warning, to last for five years, after approving the [[Foreign Office papal visit memo|sending of a memo]] written by Steven Mulvain, a 23-year-old Oxford graduate, mocking the visit.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/7804506/Diplomat-who-sent-Pope-condom-memo-given-final-warning-and-banned-from-overseas-postings.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Diplomat who sent Pope 'condom' memo given final warning and banned from overseas postings | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=6 June 2010}}</ref> Subsequently the new Government appointed liberal Catholic<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/damianthompson/100046639/lord-patten-im-like-lot-of-catholics-i-dont-agree-with-everything-the-vatican-says/ | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Lord Patten: 'I'm like lot of Catholics. I don't agree with everything the Vatican says' | date=8 July 2010}}</ref> [[Chris Patten|Lord Patten]] to get the visit back on track following a series of setbacks.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/7803820/Lord-Patten-will-co-ordinate-Pope-Benedict-XVIs-trip-to-Britain.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Lord Patten will co-ordinate Pope Benedict XVI's trip to Britain | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=4 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ticketed events===\nThere were three specific ticketed events open to the public during the Pope's visit. These were a [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in [[Bellahouston Park]], Glasgow, on the afternoon of Thursday 16 September, an evening prayer vigil in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], London, on Saturday 18 September, and the Mass of Beatification of John Henry Newman in Cofton Park, [[Longbridge]], Birmingham, on Sunday 19 September.\n\nIn contrast with the previous Papal visit to Britain, that of Pope John Paul II in 1982, where anyone could attend open-air events, there was tight security for the 2010 Papal visit, with all attendees required to register in advance through their parish and to attend in a group with a 'Pilgrim Leader' from that parish, who as leader had the responsibility to vouch for all members of his group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Attending-Events/How-can-I-see-the-Pope-in-the-UK |title=Article-How can I see the Pope in the UK? |publisher=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> All registered attendees received a 'Pilgrim Pass', required for admission to events. Non-Catholics were permitted to attend, by contacting their local parish.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckford |first=Martin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7873291/Non-Catholics-encouraged-to-take-part-in-Popes-visit-to-Britain.html |title=Non-Catholics encouraged to take part in Pope's visit to Britain |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe Mass of Beatification in Cofton Park was originally arranged for [[Coventry Airport]], with a capacity of up to 250,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/coventry_warwickshire/8576825.stm |title=Mass to be held at Coventry Airport by Pope Benedict |publisher=BBC News |date=19 March 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The planned event at the airport, which had seen 350,000 attend the visit of Pope John Paul II in 1982,<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WggOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l20DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6855,6458500]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref> was the subject of an Isle of Man commemorative stamp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/catholiclife/2010/08/13/newman-and-papal-visit-receive-stamp-of-approval/ |title=Newman and papal visit receive stamp of approval |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> However the event was switched to the much smaller Cofton Park, [[Longbridge]], a switch that the church denied was to reduce costs, instead stating that Cofton Park had a greater connection to Newman, who had lived in the area and walked around the park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10509127 |title=Pope's UK visit 'could cost taxpayers \u00a312m' |work=BBC News |date=5 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Costs===\nThe visit of the Pope was the first state visit of a Pope to Britain; the visit of his predecessor, Pope John Paul II, had been a pastoral visit, and as such the British government did not pay the costs of that visit, although expenses were incurred by local governments in areas that he visited.<ref name=visit1982>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Js8fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BNkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3067,6922073|title=The Fort Scott Tribune - Google News Archive Search|website=News.google.com|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe final cost to the British taxpayer (excluding policing costs) of the visit was \u00a310 million.<ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news|author=Riazat Butt, religious affairs correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/oct/28/catholic-church-papal-visit-uk |title=Catholic church struggles with cost of pope's visit to UK |work=The Guardian |date=28 October 2010 |accessdate=5 December 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=bbcCosts>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11305217 |title=David Cameron offers 'warm welcome' to Pope in video |work=BBC News |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The cost to the taxpayer was criticised, with a [[ComRes]] poll showing that 76% of people in the UK agreed with the statement that 'The Pope is a religious figure so the taxpayer should not be contributing to the costs of his visit'.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://campaigndirector.moodia.com/Client/Theos/Files/TheosPopePoll.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714113841/http://campaigndirector.moodia.com/Client/Theos/Files/TheosPopePoll.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2011  }}</ref> The cost was defended by the Archbishop of Westminster, leader of the Catholic Church in England and Wales, who said that it was right for the government to pay for official State Visits,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11191386 |title=Archbishop says UK taxpayer should help fund Pope visit |work=BBC News |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> as well as by Lord Patten, who said that the cost compared favourably with the \u00a320 million spent on the [[2009 G-20 London Summit]].<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i399yZzlQndOhF_77tHM7TeLAMEwD9I3OCP81]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}</ref> The visit was predicted to cost Edinburgh City council \u00a3400,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blackley |first=Michael |url=http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/topstories/Pope39s-visit-to-Edinburgh-will.6456024.jp |title=Pope's visit to Edinburgh will cost city \u00a3400k - Edinburgh Evening News |publisher=edinburghnews.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe financial benefits as well as costs of the Papal visit were reported, with the councillor coordinating the visit to Birmingham, which incurred \u00a380,000 in direct costs, estimated before the event a \u00a312.5 million boost to the city,<ref>{{cite news |author=Neil Elkes |url=http://www.birminghampost.net/dailybulletin/news2/2010/09/07/pope-visit-worth-12-5-million-to-birmingham-s-economy-65233-27221936/ |title=Pope visit worth \u00a312.5 million to Birmingham's economy |work=Birmingham Post |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> while Scott Taylor of Glasgow City Marketing Bureau said that there was a direct \u00a34.25m benefit to Glasgow, with further valuable publicity from the resultant media coverage of the city.\n\nIt was announced in July that attendees at events would be charged for a compulsory 'Pilgrim Pack', including commemorative items, in order to fund transport costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/07/14/faithful-urged-to-apply-as-soon-as-possible-for-papal-visit-places/ |title=Catholics urged to apply as soon as possible for papal visit places |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=14 July 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The costs were \u00a35 for the Hyde Park vigil (which did not include transport), \u00a325 to attend the Cofton Park event and \u00a320 to attend Bellahouston Park Mass.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckford |first=Martin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8000247/Pope-visit-Church-blames-early-start-for-low-ticket-sales.html |title=Pope visit: Church blames early start for low ticket sales |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref> The \u00a320 charge for Bellahouston Park was levied on the parish, which had discretion as to whether it recouped the cost directly from attendees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/content/download/9874/64535/file/PAPAL%20MASS%20BELLAHOUSTON%20FAQS.pdf|format=PDF|title=Papal Mass \u2013 Bellahouston Park : Thursday 16th September 2010 : Frequently Asked Questions|website=Thepapalvisit.org.uk|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309071414/http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/content/download/9874/64535/file/PAPAL%20MASS%20BELLAHOUSTON%20FAQS.pdf|archive-date=9 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The charges were said to be the first ever levied for attending Papal events,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/07/28/catholics-pay-attend-big-events-england-popes-visit-september/ |title=Pilgrims must pay to attend 2 big events in England during pope's visit in September |work=Fox News |date=7 April 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> and came amid reports that the church was \u00a32.6 million short of its donation target.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/catholic-church-struggles-to-raise-funds-for-popes-visit-2052311.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Catholic Church struggles to raise funds for Pope's visit | first=Jerome | last=Taylor | date=14 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe cost to the Catholic Church was \u00a310 million,<ref name=\"guardian1\"/><ref name=bbcCosts /> against the \u00a37 million published on the Papal Visit website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/catholic-church-struggles-to-raise-funds-for-popes-visit-2052311.html |title=Catholic Church struggles to raise funds for Pope's visit |work=The Independent |date=14 August 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London |first=Jerome |last=Taylor}}</ref> The bulk of the \u00a37m, \u00a35.2m was for staging the three large-scale public events, a further \u00a30.6m for three smaller pastoral events, with the remaining \u00a31.2m covering evangelism, planning and communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thepapalvisit.com/Donate/Why-does-the-Church-need-to-raise-7m-and-what-will-it-be-spent-on |title=Article-Why does the Church need to raise \u00a37m and what will it be spent on? |work=Thepapalvisit.com |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> \u00a31.1 million was raised through a [[Pentecost]] Sunday special collection in churches and \u00a34m from wealthy individual donors. As of November 2010 the church had a \u00a33.5m shortfall, due to be repaid to the Government by April 2011.<ref name=\"guardian1\"/>\n\n==Visit==\n\n===Scotland===\n\n====16 September====\nPope Benedict XVI began his official visit in [[Scotland]] at [[Edinburgh Airport]] on 16 September, where he was greeted by [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] and the Archbishops of [[Vincent Nichols|Westminster]] and [[Keith O'Brien|St Andrews and Edinburgh]]. He then met [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] for the first time at [[Holyrood Palace]] in [[Edinburgh]], the Queen's official residence in Scotland, with the ceremonial [[Guard of honour]] formed by the [[Royal Regiment of Scotland]], the [[Royal Company of Archers]] and the [[High Constables and Guard of Honour of the Palace of Holyroodhouse|High Constables of Holyroodhouse]].\n\nIn his speech at Holyrood Palace, the Pope associated [[State atheism|atheist extremism]] with [[Nazism]], causing controversy.<ref name=audiencequeen>{{cite web|url=https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/speeches/2010/september/documents/hf_ben-xvi_spe_20100916_incontro-autorita_en.html |title=Audience with H.M. The Queen and State Reception Address of His Holiness Benedict XVI |publisher=Vatican.va |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11332515 Row after Pope's remarks on atheism and Nazis] ''[[BBC News]]'', 16 September 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/297690 Fury as Pope appears to equate UK atheism with Nazism] ''Digital Journal'', 17 September 2010</ref><ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/Religion/post/2010/09/pope-benedict-atheists-nazis-richard-dawkins/1 Atheist Dawkins rages at pope tying godless, Nazis] ''[[USA Today]]'', 17 September 2010</ref> The Pope said:\n{{cquote|Even in our own lifetime, we can recall how [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and her leaders stood against a [[Nazi Germany|Nazi tyranny]] that wished to eradicate [[God]] from society and denied our [[humanism|common humanity]] to many, especially the [[Jews]], who were thought unfit to live. I also recall the regime\u2019s attitude to Christian pastors and religious who spoke the truth in love, opposed the Nazis and paid for that opposition with their lives. As we reflect on the sobering lessons of the atheist extremism of the twentieth century, let us never forget how the exclusion of God, religion and virtue from public life leads ultimately to a truncated vision of man and of society and thus to a \u201creductive vision of the person and his destiny\u201d<ref name=\"audiencequeen\" />}}\n\nA parade for [[Saint Ninian]]'s day was held at 11am, the route beginning on Regent Road, Edinburgh, and proceeding along [[Princes Street]]. Attendance was open to all, with a parade of school children and figures from Scotland's Christian history, in honour of St Ninian of Galloway, who brought Christianity to Scotland from Rome in the fifth century. After the parade, which was attended by around 125,000 people, the Pope proceeded by Popemobile <ref name=popemobile>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Popemobile-Routes |title=Pope Benedict XVI-Popemobile Routes |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> to have lunch with [[Keith O'Brien|Cardinal O'Brien]] at his home before travelling by car to [[Glasgow]].\n\nThe Pope was greeted by the [[Mario Conti|Archbishop of Glasgow]] for the ticketed Mass of the Feast of St Ninian in [[Bellahouston Park]]. [[Susan Boyle]] and [[Pop Idol]] winner [[Michelle McManus]] performed before the start of the mass.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} Attendance was around 65,000 people.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cramb |first=Auslan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8007705/Pope-visit-thousands-make-the-pilgrimage-to-Bellahouston-Park.html |title=Pope visit: thousands make the pilgrimage to Bellahouston Park |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref> The Pope flew from [[Glasgow Airport]] to London [[Heathrow airport]] that evening.<ref name=itinerary>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Events-Timeline |title=Article-Events Timeline / 2010 Visit |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===England===\n\n====17 September====\nOn the second day of his visit to the United Kingdom the Pope began the day with a private Mass in the chapel at [[54 Parkside]], Wimbledon, south west London, the official residence of the [[Nunciature to Great Britain|Apostolic Nunciature to Great Britain]]. His first public engagement was a celebration of Catholic education with a visit to address educators and students at [[St Mary's University, Twickenham]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stmarys.ac.uk/about/papal-visit/overview.aspx|title=The 2010 Papal Visit &#124; St Mary's University, Twickenham |publisher=Stmarys.ac.uk |date=17 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> which was followed by a meeting with people of faith in the University's Waldegrave Drawing Room.\n\nHe became the first Pope to enter [[Lambeth Palace]], where he met the [[Rowan Williams|Archbishop of Canterbury]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} He made the journey from Lambeth Palace to the [[Palace of Westminster]] by Popemobile,<ref name=popemobile /> making an Address to Civil Society from the spot in [[Westminster Hall]] where [[Thomas More|St Thomas More]] died a martyr's death in 1535, being accused of high treason for holding to his Catholic faith in refusing to acknowledge the validity of the [[First Succession Act|Act of Succession]].\n\nIn the evening there was an ecumenical celebration of evening prayer at [[Westminster Abbey]] with representatives from all the main Christian churches including the Greek Orthodox, Coptic and Free Churches. He later venerated the tomb of [[Edward the Confessor]] at the Abbey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/press/news/news/2010/september/historic-abbey-service-for-pope |title=Historic Abbey Service for Pope |publisher=Westminster Abbey |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n====18 September====\n[[File:Hyde Park Vigil.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Pope Benedict leads the vigil in Hyde Park.]]\n[[File:Hyde Park Vigil 80000.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Some of the 80,000 attending the vigil in Hyde Park.]]\nThe Pope began the day with meetings with [[David Cameron]], Prime Minister, [[Nick Clegg]], as Deputy Prime Minister, and [[Harriet Harman]], Acting Leader of the Opposition. This was followed with morning Mass in [[Westminster Cathedral]]. In his sermon, the Pope referenced [[Catholic sexual scandal in the United Kingdom|sexual abuse by priests]], saying: \"Here, too, I think of the immense suffering caused by the abuse of children, especially within the church and by her ministers. Above all, I express my deep sorrow to the innocent victims of these unspeakable crimes\", saying \"I also acknowledge with you the shame and humiliation which all of us have suffered because of these sins\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-sermon-westminster-cathedral |title=Pope Benedict XVI's sermon at Westminster Cathedral |work=The Guardian |date= 18 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nAfter Mass, the Pope used the middle part of the day to meet five victims of child sex abuse at the Apostolic Nunciature, apologising to them and describing the Church's measures to protect young people.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pigott |first=Robert |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11361749 |title=What has the Pope's visit achieved? 19 September 2010 |work=BBC News |date=19 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The meeting had been planned before the Pope's visit, and time was left free in his schedule to allow for it.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn the evening the Pope visited St Peter's Residence for Older People, run by [[Little Sisters of the Poor]]. The Pope travelled to the day's main event, the ticketed Hyde Park Prayer Vigil on the Eve of the Beatification of Cardinal Newman, by Popemobile.<ref name=popemobile /> The vigil was attended by 80,000 people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2010/09/19/the-pope-apologises-to-abuse-victims-as-80-000-pray-in-london-park-86908-22572592/ |title=The Pope apologises to abuse victims as 80,000 pray in London park |work=The Daily Record |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> The Pope's speech described Newman's life's work \"as a struggle against the growing tendency to view religion as a purely private and subjective matter, a question of personal opinion\", stating that it was a lesson for today, in which \"an intellectual and moral relativism threatens to sap the very foundations of our society\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/09/18/papal-visit-2010-popes-address-at-hyde-park-vigil-full-text/ |title=Papal Visit 2010: Pope\u2019s Address at Hyde Park Vigil \u2013 full text |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=18 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n====19 September====\n[[File:Stage preparations, Cofton Park, 090910, cropped.JPG|thumb|right|Stage being prepared for ceremony in Cofton Park]]\nThe final day of the Pope's visit saw the Pope fly by helicopter from London to [[Birmingham]] for the main event of his visit, the [[beatification]] of [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[John Henry Newman]] in [[Cofton Park]] in Birmingham. Local residents were required to carry vehicle passes as well as to carry proof of identity in order to leave their own homes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peek |first=Sitala |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-11303899 |title=Pope's visit: historic event or one to avoid? |work=BBC News |date=15 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> Attendance at the event was approximately 55,000,<ref>{{cite web |last=Hesketh |first=Jane |url=http://www.itv.com/central-west/pope-at-cofton-park51831/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127024240/http://www.itv.com/central-west/pope-at-cofton-park51831/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 January 2013 |title=Central Regional News (ITV Central Tonight) - ITV Local |publisher=Itv.com |date=19 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010 }}</ref> a figure said to have been reduced by the requirement to arrive at the location between 3am and 7am on special coaches for the 10am start.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/uk/administration-problems-blamed-for-pope-visit-ticket-slump-14947215.html |title='Administration problems' blamed for Pope visit ticket slump |work=Belfast Telegraph |date=13 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Cofton Park Mass was followed by a private visit to [[Birmingham Oratory]], founded by John Henry Newman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Itinerary/19-September-2010/The-Birmingham-Oratory |title=The Birmingham Oratory |work=Thepapalvisit.org.uk |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920163138/http://www.thepapalvisit.org.uk/2010-Visit/Visit-Event-Information/Itinerary/19-September-2010/The-Birmingham-Oratory |archive-date=20 September 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The visit was preceded by controversy due to the exiling of three priests to monasteries in separate parts of the world.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7956204/Popes-visit-could-be-overshadowed-by-exile-of-Birmingham-priests.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope's visit could be overshadowed by exile of Birmingham priests | first=Martin | last=Beckford | date=21 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe visit concluded with lunch and a meeting with the bishops of England, Scotland and Wales at [[St Mary's College, Oscott]]. The Pope gave a final speech at [[Birmingham Airport, England|Birmingham Airport]], before departing for [[Rome]] on a chartered [[Alitalia]] Airbus A320. [[British Airways]], as UK flag carrier, would have been the usual choice for a state Papal visit, but they were reportedly rejected due to concerns about strikes.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Other events===\nThe Pope's schedule reportedly included free time to allow for the 83-year-old to take naps.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/popes-uk-visit-schedule-to-contain-nap-breaks-2055909.html | location=London | work=The Independent | title=Pope's UK visit schedule to contain nap breaks | first=Jerome | last=Taylor | date=18 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn conjunction with the visit, an exhibition of [[Sistine Chapel#Raphael's tapestries|Raphael's tapestries]] for the [[Sistine Chapel]] took place at London's [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] from 8 September to 17 October 2010 where they were displayed for the first time alongside the [[Raphael cartoons]] used to make them; the cartoons having been in the British [[Royal Collection]] since 1623. This followed a reported scaling-back of earlier plans for a large exhibition of Vatican artworks at London's [[Royal Academy]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/damianthompson/100047995/popes-visit-what-happened-to-the-major-exhibition-of-vatican-treasures-at-the-royal-academy/ | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope's visit: What happened to the major exhibition of Vatican treasures at the Royal Academy? | date=21 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Anti-terrorism arrests==\nOn 17 September 2010 the [[Metropolitan Police]] arrested five street cleaners under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] in a pre-dawn raid at a London cleaning depot, in a suspected terrorist plot against the Pope on the second day of his state visit; a sixth person was arrested later in the day at his home \"on suspicion of the commission, preparation or instigation of acts of terrorism\".<ref>{{Cite news| title = Six held over Pope terror alert | date = 17 September 2010 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11346001 | work = BBC News | accessdate = 17 September 2010}}</ref> The men, aged between 26 and 50, had been working as street cleaners for contractors [[Veolia Environnement]], on behalf of [[Westminster City Council]] and were based at the Chiltern Street depot in [[Marylebone]].\n\nThe suspects were questioned at an unidentified London police station. The police did not uncover any hazardous items during an initial search of the business premises and other properties.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i399yZzlQndOhF_77tHM7TeLAMEwD9I9RPO00 | location=London | agency=Associated Press | title=6 arrested in UK in alleged terror threat to pope | first=Nicole | last=Winfield | date=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to police some of the suspects were thought to be immigrants to Britain, from a variety of nations including a number from Algeria.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/8010002/Pope-visit-sixth-man-arrested-over-alleged-assassination-plot.html | location=London | work=The Telegraph | title=Pope visit: sixth man arrested over alleged assassination plot | first=Duncan | last=Gardham | date=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nAll the men were released without charge before the Pope's visit ended. It turned out they were arrested after joking about how the [[Popemobile]] could not withstand an [[Rocket-propelled grenade|RPG]] attack.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Response==\n\n===Support===\n[[File:Flag of the Vatican City flying in Bradford (21st September 2010).jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Flag of Vatican City]] flying in [[Bradford]], [[West Yorkshire]] in honour of the papal visit.]]\nThe visit saw support from a range of people and organisations, including several leaders within other religions. The President of the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]] UK, Rafiq Hayat stated that \"Religious leaders have a pivotal role to play in promoting peace and serving humanity. Indeed religions have far more commonalities than differences and we welcome moves that will help forge unity and foster greater understanding.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sys-con.com/node/1537040|title=UK Muslim Leader Welcomes Visit by Pope|date= 17 September 2010|accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nVivian Wineman, President of the [[Board of Deputies of British Jews]], said \"In an age where scepticism and ill-will towards religion is rising, it will be an excellent opportunity to demonstrate that there is much to unite people of faith and much that can be achieved when we work together for the greater good not only of our members, but for society as a whole.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcdow.org.uk/papalvisit/blog/?25|title=Papal visit to Great Britain|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=15 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928133035/http://www.rcdow.org.uk/papalvisit/blog/?25|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMedia coverage of the visit, which was largely critical before the event, was more positive during and following the Pope's visit. A BBC News correspondent noted that 'there was a tangible sense of relief, even of euphoria, among Pope Benedict's entourage during the return flight to Rome from Birmingham'.<ref>{{cite news|last=Willey |first=David |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-11372501 |title=Pope's visit is deemed to challenge stereotypes |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=20 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition===\n{{Further|Anti-Catholicism in the United Kingdom|Criticism of the Catholic Church}}\n[[File:2010 protest the pope rally.png|thumb|right|Protest during the Pope's visit]]\n\nThe visit was opposed by a range of people and organisations including some Protestants, LGBT and secular groups due to a number of reasons, such as the Church's policies on the [[ordination of women]], [[Homosexuality and Roman Catholicism|homosexuality]], [[Catholic contraception|contraception]] and [[Roman Catholic Church and AIDS|AIDS]], as well as complaints over [[Catholic sex abuse cases|historical sexual abuse of children by Catholic priests]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|last=Wynne |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/the-pope/7981933/Public-believes-taxpayers-should-not-fund-papal-visit.html |title=Public believes taxpayers should not fund papal visit |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=5 September 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2010/06/03/church-costs-for-popes-visit-out-of-control/ |title=Church costs for Pope\u2019s visit \u2018out of control\u2019 - from Pink News |work=Pink News |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> Former DUP leader [[Ian Paisley]] (known for his staunch [[Anti-Catholicism]] in [[Northern Ireland]]) called the visit a \"mistake\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10484122 |title=Pope Benedict XVI UK visit a 'mistake' says Ian Paisley |work=BBC News |date=2 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> and the principal of Scotland's [[Free Church Training College]] said the visit airbrushed the [[Protestant Reformation]] out of history and dishonoured reformer and nationalist [[John Knox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2010/07/14/faithful-urged-to-apply-as-soon-as-possible-for-papal-visit-places/ |title=Catholics urged to apply as soon as possible for papal visit places |work=Catholicherald.co.uk |date=14 July 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref> On the eve of the visit, a letter by 50 public figures argued that the Pope's tour should not have been accorded the status of a state visit.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/15/pope-uk-state-visit-protest Pope's visit: pontiff should not be 'honoured' with state visit] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 15 September 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/15/harsh-judgments-on-pope-religion |title=Letter by 50 public figures for not giving the honour of state to Pope |work=The Guardian |date= 15 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nA number of groups, including the [[British Humanist Association]] and the [[National Secular Society]] organised a campaign of protests against the visit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.protest-the-pope.org.uk/ |title=Protest The Pope |publisher=Protest The Pope |accessdate=18 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813034024/http://www.protest-the-pope.org.uk/ |archivedate=13 August 2010  }}</ref> The Roman Catholic [[pressure group]] \"Catholic Women's Ordination\" arranged for London buses to carry advertisements encouraging the Pope to \"Ordain Women Now\"<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/22/london-bus-female-ordination-pope | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=London buses to carry female ordination advert during pope's visit. | first=Riazat | last=Butt | date=22 July 2010}}</ref> and also planned further unspecified lobbying action. Religious and secular correspondents noted that only 3 women appeared at Lambeth Palace to support the ordination of women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-womens-ordination.org.uk/news.htm#Pope |title=Local Groups |work=Catholic-womens-ordination.org.uk |date= |accessdate=17 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Richard dawkins speaking at the protest the pope rally 2010.png|thumb|right|[[Richard Dawkins]] speaking at the protest, with [[Peter Tatchell]] on the left at the back.]]\n[[Richard Dawkins]] gave a speech to over 10,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-protest|title=Protest the Pope rally sees 10,000 march through London's streets|first=Tracy|last=Mcveigh|date=18 September 2010|accessdate=26 November 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> people at the \"Protest the Pope\" rally, declaring the pope \"an enemy of humanity\", and countering the Pope's claim that [[the holocaust]] was the result of atheism by arguing that [[Hitler]] was a Roman Catholic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://richarddawkins.net/articles/521113-ratzinger-is-an-enemy-of-humanity |title=Dawkins speech |publisher=Richarddawkins.net |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Science |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/punctuated-equilibrium/2010/sep/20/1 |title=Richard Dawkins' unedited speech at 'Protest the Pope' march in London |work=The Guardian |date= 20 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref> Dawkins had previously supported a call for the Pope's arrest for \"crimes against humanity\", an idea first proposed by [[Christopher Hitchens]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://richarddawkins.net/videos/5434-christopher-hitchens-arrest-the-pope | title=Christopher Hitchens: Arrest The Pope!}}</ref> and described by a former editor of the ''[[Catholic Herald]]'' as \"lunatic\",<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8614232.stm | work=BBC News | title=Dawkins backs plan to arrest Pope | date=13 April 2010}}</ref> and human rights lawyer [[Geoffrey Robertson]] was reported to have looked at options to [[Geoffrey Robertson#Putting Pope Benedict XVI on trial|charge the Pope]] over his alleged cover-up of sexual abuse in the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2010/apr/13/pope-prosecution-dawkins |title=The pope should stand trial |work=The Guardian |date= 13 April 2010|accessdate=18 September 2010 |location=London |first=Richard |last=Dawkins}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, the UK government announced plans to change the law on universal jurisdiction to prevent the issue of an arrest warrant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/295022 |title=UK government acts to prevent arrest of Pope |publisher=Digitaljournal.com |date=23 July 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Attempts to make a citizen's arrest on the Pope were abandoned by [[Peter Tatchell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/peter-tatchell-scraps-idea-of-making-citizens-arrest-on-the-pope-2074273.html |title=Peter Tatchell scraps idea of making citizen's arrest on the Pope |work=The Independent |date= 9 September 2010|accessdate=17 September 2010 |location=London |first=Jerome |last=Taylor}}</ref> Members of [[Muslims Against Crusades]] protested against the Pope in London.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Multiple authors|title=Pope Benedict XVI's UK visit: Day three|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-london|accessdate=10 April 2016|work=The Guardian|agency=Reuters|date=18 September 2010}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' reported that around 10,000 protesters marched in London against the Pope's visit on 18 September 2010.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tracy Mcveigh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/sep/18/pope-benedict-xvi-protest |title=Protest the Pope rally sees 10,000 march through London's streets |work=The Guardian |date= 18 September 2010|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nThe [[BBC]] marked the visit with documentaries including:<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mandrake/7866684/Pope-Benedict-XVI-about-to-be-put-on-trial-by-the-BBC.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Pope Benedict XVI about to be put on trial by the BBC | first=Tim | last=Walker | date=2 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/03/bbc-papal-visit | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=BBC to mark Pope's UK visit with documentary on clerical abuse scandals | first=Tara | last=Conlan | date=3 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n* ''Vatican: The Hidden World'', a profile of the [[Holy See|Vatican]] with unprecedented access given\n* ''The Real Joseph Ratzinger'', a papal profile\n*''Newman: Saint or Sinner?'', a documentary about [[Cardinal Newman]]\n*''Benedict - Trials of a Pope'', a documentary about the life of the Pope<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00ttj16 |title=Benedict: Trials of a Pope |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Catholicism|Christianity}}\n*[[List of journeys of Pope Benedict XVI]]\n*[[Roman Catholicism in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Foreign Office papal visit memo]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikinews|Pope Benedict XVI heads to the UK amid protests}}\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111119175338/http://thepapalvisit.co.uk/ Apostolic journey to Britain] - official website from [[Catholic Church in England and Wales]]\n*[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/travels/2010/index_regno-unito_en.htm Apostolic Journey to the United Kingdom] - official website from the [[Holy See]]\n\n<br />\n{{Benedict XVI}}\n{{Elizabeth II}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pope Benedict Xvi's Visit To The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:Pope Benedict XVI]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of the Holy See]]\n[[Category:History of Christianity in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2010 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2010 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Foreign trips by popes|Benedict XVI, United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Holy See\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic visits to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:September 2010 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEngland:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_Benedict_XVI%27s_visit_to_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes\n| image = OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes cover.jpg\n| caption = Cover art for ''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes''. The artwork is done by Justin Chan.\n| developer = [[Capybara Games]]\n| publisher = Outright Games{{efn|Published digitally by [[Cartoon Network Games]]}}\n| director = Dan Vader\n| designer = Dan Vader<br />Arielle Grimes\n| programmer = Dave Hill<br />Kenneth Yeung<br />Hubert Wong<br />Drew Grainge\n| artist = Kelly Smith<br />Mike Nguyen\n| writer = Dan Vader\n| composer = [[Doseone]]\n| series = \n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One''' January 23, 2018<br />'''Nintendo Switch''' November 2, 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure]], [[beat 'em up]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes''''' is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[beat 'em up]] video game developed by [[Capybara Games]] and published by [[Cartoon Network Games]]. It is based on the show ''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]'' and was released digitally on January 23, 2018<ref name=releasedate>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/4/16849252/capy-games-ok-ko-lets-play-heroes-release-date-cartoon-network |title=Capy Games' next game, Cartoon Network's OK K.O.!, launches Jan. 23 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=January 4, 2018 |accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], with a port to the [[Nintendo Switch]] launching physically in 2019.\n\n==Plot==\nWhen [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Lord Boxman|Lord Boxman]] takes away all the levels of the heroes' pow cards, [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#K.O.|K.O.]] must set things right and must learn at heart that he is a true hero.<ref name=DL>{{cite web|author=Dino-Ray Ramos |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/ok-k-o-lets-be-heroes-season-2-cartoon-network-video-game-1202221752/ |title='OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes' Set For Season 2 With New Console Video Game |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nK.O. is controlled when fighting against villains. The player can use moves such as an uppercut, punch combo, low kick, etc. The player can collect their stats after defeating all enemies to earn new moves such as a charge punch, a controllable fist, and a stronger uppercut.\n\nDuring combat, taking damage or dealing damage will raise a bar towards using a special ability called a Powie Zowie, where the player will summon the character in the card and get help. Some examples include [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Radicles|Rad]], who allows players to levitate and shoot beams, and [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Carol|Carol]], who will appear and start doing a combo in front of the player.\n\n==Development==\nOn December 7, 2017, the first trailer for the game was released.<ref name=YouTube2>{{cite web|author=Cartoon Network|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iYesJNTmUV8 |title=OK K.O.! - Let's Play Heroes First Official Trailer! - Cartoon Network |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nUpon release, ''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes'' received mostly positive reviews. A review by PlayStation LifeStyle remarked that the game \"shows that licensed kids cartoon adaptations don\u2019t have to be mediocre, and that they can be filled with the same charm as the television shows that made them beloved in the first place.\", but was criticized for its repetitive combat.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Treese |first1=Tyler |title=OK K.O.! Let\u2019s Play Heroes Review \u2013 How Licensed Games Should Be (PS4) |url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2018/02/22/ok-ko-lets-play-heroes-review-great-licensed-game/#/slide/1 |website=PlayStation LifeStyle |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt7478670}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Cartoon Network video games}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on television series]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network video games]]\n\n\n{{action-adventure-videogame-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes\n| image = OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes cover.jpg\n| caption = Cover art for ''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes''. The artwork is done by Justin Chan.\n| developer = [[Capybara Games]]\n| publisher = Outright Games{{efn|Published digitally by [[Cartoon Network Games]]}}\n| director = Dan Vader\n| designer = Dan Vader<br />Arielle Grimes\n| programmer = Dave Hill<br />Kenneth Yeung<br />Hubert Wong<br />Drew Grainge\n| artist = Kelly Smith<br />Mike Nguyen\n| writer = Dan Vader\n| composer = [[Doseone]]\n| series = \n| platforms = {{Unbulleted list|[[Microsoft Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]|[[Nintendo Switch]]}}\n| released = '''Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4, Xbox One''' January 23, 2018<br />'''Nintendo Switch''' November 2, 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure]], [[beat 'em up]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes''''' is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[beat 'em up]] video game developed by [[Capybara Games]] and published by [[Cartoon Network Games]]. It is based on the show ''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]'' and was released digitally on January 23, 2018<ref name=releasedate>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/1/4/16849252/capy-games-ok-ko-lets-play-heroes-release-date-cartoon-network |title=Capy Games' next game, Cartoon Network's OK K.O.!, launches Jan. 23 |publisher=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=January 4, 2018 |accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]], with a port to the [[Nintendo Switch]] launching physically in 2019.\n\n==Plot==\nWhen [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Lord Boxman|Lord Boxman]] takes away all the levels of the heroes' pow cards, [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#K.O.|K.O.]] must set things right and must learn at heart that he is a true hero.<ref name=DL>{{cite web|author=Dino-Ray Ramos |url=https://deadline.com/2017/12/ok-k-o-lets-be-heroes-season-2-cartoon-network-video-game-1202221752/ |title='OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes' Set For Season 2 With New Console Video Game |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nK.O. is controlled when fighting against villains. The player can use moves such as an uppercut, punch combo, low kick, etc. The player can collect their stats after defeating all enemies to earn new moves such as a charge punch, a controllable fist, and a stronger uppercut.\n\nDuring combat, taking damage or dealing damage will raise a bar towards using a special ability called a Powie Zowie, where the player will summon the character in the card and get help. Some examples include [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Radicles|Rad]], who allows players to levitate and shoot beams, and [[List of OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes characters#Carol|Carol]], who will appear and start doing a combo in front of the player.\n\n==Development==\nOn December 7, 2017, the first trailer for the game was released.<ref name=YouTube2>{{cite web|author=Cartoon Network|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iYesJNTmUV8 |title=OK K.O.! - Let's Play Heroes First Official Trailer! - Cartoon Network |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=December 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nUpon release, ''OK K.O.! Let's Play Heroes'' received mostly positive reviews. A review by PlayStation LifeStyle remarked that the game \"shows that licensed kids cartoon adaptations don\u2019t have to be mediocre, and that they can be filled with the same charm as the television shows that made them beloved in the first place.\", but was criticized for it's repetitive combat.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Treese |first1=Tyler |title=OK K.O.! Let\u2019s Play Heroes Review \u2013 How Licensed Games Should Be (PS4) |url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2018/02/22/ok-ko-lets-play-heroes-review-great-licensed-game/#/slide/1 |website=PlayStation LifeStyle |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt7478670}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Cartoon Network video games}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on television series]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network video games]]\n\n\n{{action-adventure-videogame-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OK_K.O.!_Let%27s_Play_Heroes"}
{"title_page": "Laurie Maher", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Laurie Maher\n| honorific-suffix = OAM\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| office = Mayor of [[Gosford City Council|Gosford]]\n| term_start = 2007\n| term_end = 24 September 2012\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Lawrie McKinna]]\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n \n| party = Central Coast First<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccbusinessreview.com.au/articles/197|title=Central Coast Business Review - Regional industrial, retail, property and tourism news.|publisher=Central Coast Business Review}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Laurence Joseph \"Laurie\" Maher''' is the former mayor of [[Gosford City Council]]<ref name=retire/>  and the former CEO of [[Coast Shelter]], a non-profit homelessness service assisting people in the [[Central Coast, New South Wales|Central Coast]] region of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\nMaher founded the organisation in 1992 and held the position of CEO until his retirement in July 2018. He served as the Mayor of Gosford, serving four terms. Maher was first elected to Council in 2004, elected as Mayor in 2007.<ref name=oam/> Maher retired as mayor in 2012.<ref name=retire>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-25/mayor-retires/4091142 \"Gosford Mayor prepares to retire.\"] ''ABC News''. 25 June 2012. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> In 2009, Maher was presented with an Award for Services to the Aboriginal Community by the Darkinjung Local Aboriginal Land Council.<ref>[http://www.darkinjung.com.au/ContentFiles/Darkinjung/Documents/Newsletters/Third%20Edition.pdf ''Darkinjung News''] Vol. 1, Issue 3. September 2009. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> In 2010 Maher was awarded with [[Order of Australia]] Award for his service to the community of Gosford through social welfare and local government organisations.<ref name=oam>[https://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1142025&search_type=simple&showInd=true \"MAHER, Laurence Joseph.\"] ''www.itsanhonour.gov.au''. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2010/Media%20Notes%20OAM%20(M-R)%20(final).pdf \"Medal (OAM) of the Order of Australia in the General Division.\"] ''www.gg.gov.au''. 2010. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> He has also been the recipient of the NSW Community Service Award.<ref name=oam/>\n\n==Mayor of Gosford==\nIn 2011, Maher agreed to a proposed merger of Gosford and Wyong councils, stating the councils would become more effective in dealing with the needs of the regions as a single operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/coast-is-clear-for-merger/story-e6frfkp9-1226064763754|title=Coast is clear for merger|publisher=News.com.au|date=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Historical Sex Offences==\n\nFollowing a series of complaints made to the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Strikeforce Eckersly was established by the Nepean Police Area Command towards the end of 2016. On the 20th of April 2020, it was announced that a 9th man had been charged with historical sex offences with the Newcastle Herald stating \"Strike force investigators issued a Court Attendance Notice (CAN) for the offences of four counts of buggery, three counts of indecent assault on male, and six counts of sexual assault knowing no consent given to an 81-year-old man on Thursday 5 March 2020.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/6727954/central-coast-man-to-face-court-over-alleged-historical-sex-offences/ |website=Newcastle Herald |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Laurie Maher was named the following day by NBN news as the ninth person to face court over allegedly misconduct committed at Mt Penang Training School. The alleged offences took place between 1977 and 1988.<ref>{{cite news |title=Laurie Maher Charged with Historical Sex Offences |url=https://www.nbnnews.com.au/2020/04/21/laurie-maher-charged-with-historical-sex-offences/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=NBN News |date=21 April 2020 |ref=https://www.nbnnews.com.au/2020/04/21/laurie-maher-charged-with-historical-sex-offences/}}</ref>\n\nA spokesperson from Coast Shelter stated that \"allegations predate Maher\u2019s involvement with the charity and is no longer an employee.\"\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coast Shelter]]\n*[[Gosford City Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maher, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Australia-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Laurie Maher\n| honorific-suffix = OAM\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| office = Mayor of [[Gosford City Council|Gosford]]\n| term_start = 2007\n| term_end = 24 September 2012\n| predecessor = \n| successor = [[Lawrie McKinna]]\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n \n| party = Central Coast First<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccbusinessreview.com.au/articles/197|title=Central Coast Business Review - Regional industrial, retail, property and tourism news.|publisher=Central Coast Business Review}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Laurence Joseph \"Laurie\" Maher''' is the former mayor of [[Gosford City Council]]<ref name=retire/>  and the former CEO of [[Coast Shelter]], a non-profit homelessness service assisting people in the [[Central Coast, New South Wales|Central Coast]] region of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\nMaher founded the organisation in 1992 and held the position of CEO until his retirement in July 2018. He served as the Mayor of Gosford, serving four terms. Maher was first elected to Council in 2004, elected as Mayor in 2007.<ref name=oam/> Maher retired as mayor in 2012.<ref name=retire>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-06-25/mayor-retires/4091142 \"Gosford Mayor prepares to retire.\"] ''ABC News''. 25 June 2012. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> In 2009, Maher was presented with an Award for Services to the Aboriginal Community by the Darkinjung Local Aboriginal Land Council.<ref>[http://www.darkinjung.com.au/ContentFiles/Darkinjung/Documents/Newsletters/Third%20Edition.pdf ''Darkinjung News''] Vol. 1, Issue 3. September 2009. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> In 2010 Maher was awarded with [[Order of Australia]] Award for his service to the community of Gosford through social welfare and local government organisations.<ref name=oam>[https://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1142025&search_type=simple&showInd=true \"MAHER, Laurence Joseph.\"] ''www.itsanhonour.gov.au''. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref><ref>[https://www.gg.gov.au/sites/default/files/files/honours/ad/ad2010/Media%20Notes%20OAM%20(M-R)%20(final).pdf \"Medal (OAM) of the Order of Australia in the General Division.\"] ''www.gg.gov.au''. 2010. Accessed 27 July 2016.</ref> He has also been the recipient of the NSW Community Service Award.<ref name=oam/>\n\n==Mayor of Gosford==\nIn 2011, Maher agreed to a proposed merger of Gosford and Wyong councils, stating the councils would become more effective in dealing with the needs of the regions as a single operation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/coast-is-clear-for-merger/story-e6frfkp9-1226064763754|title=Coast is clear for merger|publisher=News.com.au|date=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Historical Sex Offences==\n\nFollowing a series of complaints made to the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse, Strikeforce Eckersly was established by the Nepean Police Area Command towards the end of 2016. On the 20th of April 2020, it was announced that a 9th man had been charged with historical sex offences with the Newcastle Herald stating \"Strike force investigators issued a Court Attendance Notice (CAN) for the offences of four counts of buggery, three counts of indecent assault on male, and six counts of sexual assault knowing no consent given to an 81-year-old man on Thursday 5 March 2020.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcastleherald.com.au/story/6727954/central-coast-man-to-face-court-over-alleged-historical-sex-offences/ |website=Newcastle Herald |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> Laurie Maher was named the following day by NBN news as the ninth person to face court over allegedly misconduct committed at Mt Penang Training School. The alleged offences took place between 1977 and 1988.<ref>{{cite news |title=Laurie Maher Charged with Historical Sex Offences |url=https://www.nbnnews.com.au/2020/04/21/laurie-maher-charged-with-historical-sex-offences/ |accessdate=21 April 2020 |work=NBN News |date=21/4/20 |ref=https://www.nbnnews.com.au/2020/04/21/laurie-maher-charged-with-historical-sex-offences/}}</ref>\n\nA spokesperson from Coast Shelter stated that \"allegations predate Maher\u2019s involvement with the charity and is no longer an employee.\"\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coast Shelter]]\n*[[Gosford City Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maher, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Australia-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix cite date error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurie_Maher"}
{"title_page": "Nedyu Rachev", "text_new": "{{short description|Bulgarian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Nedyu Rachev\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1915|10|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n}}\n\n'''Nedyu Rachev''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0435\u0434\u044e \u0420\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432}}, born 4 October 1915, date of death unknown) was a Bulgarian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's sprint|sprint]] event at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ra/nedyu-rachev-1.html |title=Nedyu Rachev Olympic Results |accessdate=13 July 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rachev, Nedyu}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{Bulgaria-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bulgarian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Nedyu Rachev\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1915|10|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = \n| ridertype      = \n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n}}\n\n'''Nedyu Rachev''' ({{lang-bg|\u041d\u0435\u0434\u044e \u0420\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432}}, born 4 October 1915, date of death unknown) was a Bulgarian [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1936 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's sprint|sprint]] event at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ra/nedyu-rachev-1.html |title=Nedyu Rachev Olympic Results |accessdate=13 July 2014 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rachev, Nedyu}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1936 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{Bulgaria-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nedyu_Rachev"}
{"title_page": "Panama remote controlled vehicle", "text_new": "[[File:Mastiff and Panama Remote Controlled Vehicle MOD 45159062.jpg|alt=A Mastiff fitted with Choker Mine Rollers following on behind the Panama remote control Land Rover. The vehicles are in a flat desert in Jordan with a bright blue sky. At the front of the Land Rover, about six feet off the ground, is a horizontal beam which can be lowered in front of the vehicle to scan the ground with radar. The beam is approximately three metres wide.|thumb|A [[Cougar (MRAP)|Mastiff]] fitted with Choker [[mine roller]]s following on behind the Panama Remotely Operated Vehicle which carries a ground penetrating radar used for route clearance operations.]]\n\nThe '''Panama Remotely Operated Vehicle (ROV)''' is a piece of mine-clearing equipment used by the [[British Armed Forces]].\n\n==Design==\nThe Panama ROV consists of a [[Snatch Land Rover]] modified for remote control operation, with a large piece of mine-detection equipment mounted to the front. It was created by [[Defence Equipment and Support]], part of the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], in conjunction with [[PA Consulting Group]] as a low-cost solution to mine detection in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = \u2018Panama\u2019: Groundbreaking project aids UK troops|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e53c7e8a-2cec-11e2-beb2-00144feabdc0.html|newspaper = Financial Times|date = 2012-11-12|access-date = 2016-01-25|issn = 0307-1766|first = Andrew|last = Baxter}}</ref> Before the introduction of the Panama, an average of one person every week was killed, with five or six more being severely injured.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Panama vehicle is towed behind another vehicle \u2013 usually a [[Buffalo (mine protected vehicle)|Buffalo MRAP vehicle]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|title = UV Europe 2011: Unmanned Snatch a work in progress \u2013 News \u2013 Shephard|url = https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/uv-online/uv-europe-2011-unmanned-snatch-a-work-in/|website = www.shephardmedia.com|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> It can be unhitched from the towing vehicle without the crew having to expose themselves, and remotely driven to search for explosive devices.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.lexisnexis.com.remote.slc.edu/lnacui2api/results/docview/docview.do?docLinkInd=true&risb=21_T23373215227&format=GNBFI&sort=RELEVANCE&startDocNo=1&resultsUrlKey=29_T23373215231&cisb=22_T23373215230&treeMax=true&treeWidth=0&csi=10939&docNo=5|title = Army's mobile coffin finally earns its stripes|last = Partridge|first = Chris|date = 2012-05-17|work = |access-date = 2016-01-25|via = LexisNexis Academic|newspaper = The Times|publication-place = London}}</ref> A single system consists of two Panama vehicles and a control station.<ref name=\":4\" /> They usually work as part of a Talisman team, which consists of two [[Buffalo (mine protected vehicle)|Buffalo Rummage]] and four [[Cougar (MRAP)|Mastiff]] 'Protected Eyes' vehicles; two [[Micro air vehicle|micro unmanned air vehicles]] (MUAV); two [[JCB HMEE|HMEEs]]; and two [[Foster-Miller TALON|Talon UGVs]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe vehicles are considerably cheaper than a bespoke solution, as they make use of the SN2A Snatch Land Rover, which was rendered obsolete due to poor armour protection.<ref name=\":0\" /> The military had approximately 200 of these vehicles awaiting disposal.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Protecting troops' lives in Afghanistan \u2013 UK Ministry of Defence|url = http://www.paconsulting.com/our-experience/pa-wins-top-prize-at-the-2012-mca-awards-for-life-saving-unmanned-ied-detection-system/|website = PA Consulting Group|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> The vehicle has been in use in Afghanistan since early 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = PA Consulting Group wins top prize at the 2012 MCA awards \u2013 23 April 2012|url = http://www.paconsulting.com/introducing-pas-media-site/releases/pa-consulting-group-wins-top-prize-at-the-2012-mca-awards-23-april-2012/|website = PA Consulting Group|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe project took 11 months to move from procurement decision to operational use, and cost \u00a350m in total, \u00a39m less than expected.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The use of the Snatch Land Rovers awaiting disposal, rather than a new vehicle, saves an extra \u00a38m over the length of the contract.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The programme was managed by the DE&S itself \u2013 with assistance from PA Consulting \u2013 which is unusual for procurement in the United Kingdom. However, despite the unorthodox method, the Land Rover was accepted as a solution. Lieutenant Colonel Adrian Parker of the [[Royal Engineers]] said of the choice, \"There is a whole generation of technicians who are trained in their maintenance. There is a supply chain for the parts, all the manuals are written and all those thousands of parts are already codified to [[NATO Codification System|NATO]] standards. Using our scoring system, the Snatch came top.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWalters also said that, as the operator uses a simple computer display which is familiar to computer game players, soldiers can learn to use the vehicle in just one hour.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe project, and PA Consulting Group, won the Management Consultancies Association Award for the best overall project in 2012.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Military equipment of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unmanned ground combat vehicles]]\n[[Category:Bomb disposal robots]]\n[[Category:Mine warfare countermeasures]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom defence procurement]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mastiff and Panama Remote Controlled Vehicle MOD 45159062.jpg|alt=A Mastiff fitted with Choker Mine Rollers following on behind the Panama remote control Land Rover. The vehicles are in a flat desert in Jordan with a bright blue sky. At the front of the Land Rover, about six feet off the ground, is a horizontal beam which can be lowered in front of the vehicle to scan the ground with radar. The beam is approximately three metres wide.|thumb|A [[Cougar (vehicle)|Mastiff]] fitted with Choker [[mine roller]]s following on behind the Panama Remotely Operated Vehicle which carries a ground penetrating radar used for route clearance operations.]]\n\nThe '''Panama Remotely Operated Vehicle (ROV)''' is a piece of mine-clearing equipment used by the [[British Armed Forces]].\n\n==Design==\nThe Panama ROV consists of a [[Snatch Land Rover]] modified for remote control operation, with a large piece of mine-detection equipment mounted to the front. It was created by [[Defence Equipment and Support]], part of the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], in conjunction with [[PA Consulting Group]] as a low-cost solution to mine detection in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|title = \u2018Panama\u2019: Groundbreaking project aids UK troops|url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/e53c7e8a-2cec-11e2-beb2-00144feabdc0.html|newspaper = Financial Times|date = 2012-11-12|access-date = 2016-01-25|issn = 0307-1766|first = Andrew|last = Baxter}}</ref> Before the introduction of the Panama, an average of one person every week was killed, with five or six more being severely injured.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe Panama vehicle is towed behind another vehicle \u2013 usually a [[Buffalo (mine protected vehicle)|Buffalo MRAP vehicle]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|title = UV Europe 2011: Unmanned Snatch a work in progress \u2013 News \u2013 Shephard|url = https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/uv-online/uv-europe-2011-unmanned-snatch-a-work-in/|website = www.shephardmedia.com|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> It can be unhitched from the towing vehicle without the crew having to expose themselves, and remotely driven to search for explosive devices.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.lexisnexis.com.remote.slc.edu/lnacui2api/results/docview/docview.do?docLinkInd=true&risb=21_T23373215227&format=GNBFI&sort=RELEVANCE&startDocNo=1&resultsUrlKey=29_T23373215231&cisb=22_T23373215230&treeMax=true&treeWidth=0&csi=10939&docNo=5|title = Army's mobile coffin finally earns its stripes|last = Partridge|first = Chris|date = 2012-05-17|work = |access-date = 2016-01-25|via = LexisNexis Academic|newspaper = The Times|publication-place = London}}</ref> A single system consists of two Panama vehicles and a control station.<ref name=\":4\" /> They usually work as part of a Talisman team, which consists of two [[Buffalo (mine protected vehicle)|Buffalo Rummage]] and four [[Cougar (vehicle)|Mastiff]] 'Protected Eyes' vehicles; two [[Micro air vehicle|micro unmanned air vehicles]] (MUAV); two [[JCB HMEE|HMEEs]]; and two [[Foster-Miller TALON|Talon UGVs]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe vehicles are considerably cheaper than a bespoke solution, as they make use of the SN2A Snatch Land Rover, which was rendered obsolete due to poor armour protection.<ref name=\":0\" /> The military had approximately 200 of these vehicles awaiting disposal.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Protecting troops' lives in Afghanistan \u2013 UK Ministry of Defence|url = http://www.paconsulting.com/our-experience/pa-wins-top-prize-at-the-2012-mca-awards-for-life-saving-unmanned-ied-detection-system/|website = PA Consulting Group|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref> The vehicle has been in use in Afghanistan since early 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = PA Consulting Group wins top prize at the 2012 MCA awards \u2013 23 April 2012|url = http://www.paconsulting.com/introducing-pas-media-site/releases/pa-consulting-group-wins-top-prize-at-the-2012-mca-awards-23-april-2012/|website = PA Consulting Group|access-date = 2016-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe project took 11 months to move from procurement decision to operational use, and cost \u00a350m in total, \u00a39m less than expected.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The use of the Snatch Land Rovers awaiting disposal, rather than a new vehicle, saves an extra \u00a38m over the length of the contract.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The programme was managed by the DE&S itself \u2013 with assistance from PA Consulting \u2013 which is unusual for procurement in the United Kingdom. However, despite the unorthodox method, the Land Rover was accepted as a solution. Lieutenant Colonel Adrian Parker of the [[Royal Engineers]] said of the choice, \"There is a whole generation of technicians who are trained in their maintenance. There is a supply chain for the parts, all the manuals are written and all those thousands of parts are already codified to [[NATO Codification System|NATO]] standards. Using our scoring system, the Snatch came top.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nWalters also said that, as the operator uses a simple computer display which is familiar to computer game players, soldiers can learn to use the vehicle in just one hour.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe project, and PA Consulting Group, won the Management Consultancies Association Award for the best overall project in 2012.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Military equipment of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Unmanned ground combat vehicles]]\n[[Category:Bomb disposal robots]]\n[[Category:Mine warfare countermeasures]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom defence procurement]]\n", "name_user": "Le Petit Chat", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panama_remote_controlled_vehicle"}
